The first third or so of Little Big League is warm and winning - and has some big laughs. But as it progresses, the drama becomes more sentimental and stagnant, and the film begins to drag.
Like too many sequels, it has forgotten what the first film was really about. Slickers II is about the MacGuffin instead of the characters.
Here is a wise and ambitious film about the way alcoholism affects the fabric of a marriage.
The exquisite tragic ending -- conceived musically and rhythmically as a gradually decelerating diminuendo -- is one of the pinnacles of silent cinema.

Some of Murnau's genius remains in the lighting of individual shots, and particularly in a lyrical sequence in which a man (Charles Farrell), a woman (Mary Duncan), and Murnau's camera dance through a sunlit field.
This tearjerker melodrama proved to be a big hit commercially for the popular silent star Mary Pickford.

Neilan's imagery is largely theatrical -- he seldom cuts meaningfully within scenes, he treats his locations almost as stage sets, and his idea of subtle lighting is using a narrow bar of light to illuminate the eyes of a murderess.
The most breath-stoppingly thrilling motion picture to open since the original Die Hard.
We've seen this done before, but seldom so well, or at such a high pitch of energy.

Undeniably, the picture now and again supplies that edge-of-the-seat sensation; yet, by action-adventure standards, Speed is leaden and strangely poky. It never seems to shift into overdrive and let fly.
The plot becomes so overextended, as Reeves and Hopper wage their endless public transportation battle, even the hardest Die-Harders will consider leaping off way before the final stop.

If you're inclined to pick it apart and ask a lot of questions, you'll quickly conclude that there's zero chance this kind of scenario would unfold in the real world, but it's so well done here, you just don't care.
Relentless without being overbearing, this is one likely blockbuster that doesn't feel too big for its britches. It's a friendly juggernaut.
For sheer thrills and excitement, few films can touch Speed.
In a film like this, timing is everything, and everyone from the stunt coordinators to the crew-at-large seems to have gotten it right the first time.
Reeves finally proves that not only can he act, he can be do some great stuff if he is cast and directed right.

Succeeds primarily because of De Bont's attention to detail and, specifically, the way his camera moves through the inner workings of Hopper's bombs and the various modes of transportation they theaten.
Audiences may have experienced similar stories before, but they are seldom done this well and with this level of energy.
The best action picture Hollywood has made in years.
Wyatt Earp plays as if they took Tombstone and pumped it full of hot air. It involves many of the same characters and much of the same story, but little of the tension and drama
Lawrence Kasdan's retelling of the cowboy legend reprises -- and often outdoes -- the deft mix of comedy and western lore the writer/director brought to his own Silverado.
Wyatt Earp, a biopic that lasts more than three hours and moves with the urgency of a grazing buffalo, lacks everything from a coherent dramatic structure to a clearly articulated point of view.
What works is, first of all, the DeVito performance as a driven man in a ridiculous job who loves his children but has lost his bearings.
The film's episodic nature tends to undermine its impetus and the final quarter seems tacked-on, almost like it belongs in some other movie. In short, it suffers from trying to do too much.
Topographically beautiful and historically potent.

Yasujiro Ozu's 1949 film inaugurated his majestic late period: it's here that he decisively renounces melodrama (and, indeed, most surface action of any kind) and lets his camera settle into the still, long-take contemplation.
The dysfunctional family in this film is little more than a shameless plot device to introduce a lame father/son bonding adventure.
Here is a movie with broad ambitions: It wants to be a caper, a comedy, a romance, and a showcase for MacAulay Culkin. That's too much of a stretch.
Who, exactly, is supposed to fall for this stuff?
It's so monotonously unimaginative that it practically qualifies as child abuse.
The only point to this movie is to make Macaulay a millionaire.
Culkin's performance here is so lethargic that he seems to bring the entire production down.
This isn't a masterpiece of suspense, but it has its moments and is capable of providing some light summer entertainment.
Not as satisfying as it should be.
It twists and turns in all the expected places, and almost never rises above the ordinary.
Mindless, non-taxing fun, especially if you haven't read the book.
Almost every word Jones utters is terrific. The script is good, but his delivery is what makes it.
All in all, it's a mixed bag -- but enjoyable enough to please Grisham fans.
For me, Germinal provided visual and dramatic images for 19th century history events that I only understood in an abstract way.
An extremely moving tale that points to the ultimate hopelessness of the human condition.
Big and impressive in its epic scope, Germinal nevertheless suffers from uneven acting, over-the-top histrionics and a constant dark and dour tone.
Widow's Peak is another of those sly, witty, quietly ribald comedies that have been coming out of Ireland in the last few years.
It is a small civilizing story without a big phony crisis and a manufactured climax. It's just about people we feel good to have known.
Baby's Day Out contains gags that might have worked in a Baby Herman cartoon, but in live action, with real people, real taxis and buses and streets and a real baby, they're just not funny.
It's somehow reassuring, these days, to see a movie where there's no problem Lassie can't solve.
The story may be predictable, ham-fisted and saccharine, but that's why kids (and softhearted parents) will like it.
For better or worse, "Lassie" is as safe and square as the TV show of yesteryear.
If you don't place too many demands on it, Lassie will while away your time pleasantly. But, ultimately this pup is all bark and no bite.
The plot stays simple and predictable through out the entire movie, but you never mind because it is so life affirming.
In all, pretty good family fare.
Here is a film so inviting you would love to sit in the sun with old Manolo and his friend the priest, and talk about the great matters of life. And about his daughters.
Funny and bright and most enjoyable
Although the movie runs 95 minutes, it contains nothing much in the way of information about surfing.
Pretty hard to sit through, because Brown's incessant beach boy prattle is endlessly irritating.
One of those rare bits of movie marginalia that are entirely without merit and, still, a pleasure to sit through.
Bruce Brown's loving surfing documentary sequel.
Some of it is fascinating to see, some of it is fun to hear about, but inevitably, you end up with a few earfuls more than you bargained for.
Through it all, Brown cracks wise and simply tries to provide an entertaining two hours. The film falters occasionally, but he pretty much achieves his goal.

This movie is not tightly-scripted or elegantly produced, but it is (for the most part) highly entertaining. For those who have been waiting for a sequel to Spinal Tap, this may be the best alternative.
Not as fearless and sharp-edged as it could be -- but it provides a lot of laughs, and barbecues a few sacred cows.
Fear of a Black Hat is not brilliant, but it's bright enough.
There's no plot to speak of, just gag after gag. Rap fans will likely love most of it; all others, flip a coin.

As it recounts the history of N.W.H., the film also manages to lampoon rap music and its archetypes, as well as poking fun at the venal, self-serving music-business types looking to grab easy money from the scene.
Observing how fertile the field of heavy metal music is for satire, it's disappointing to watch Airheads bumble around, desperately trying to find something funny to say.
Even Beavis and Butt-head get to call in their critique. Naturally, they think the Lone Rangers suck.
On the whole, Airheads is heavily entertaining.
It does have its moments, but I felt very ripped off that they were all shown in the trailer.
Lehmann can't seem to make up his mind if this is an outright comedy or a social satire along the line of This is Spinal Tap, which, naturally, results in virtually nothing.
This film will...be quickly forgotten by anyone unfortunate enough to sit through it.
A spoof of heavy-metal culture that at the same time respects the vitality and pent-up passion behind it.
An old-fashioned, high-tech, fun time at the movies.
On the basis of stunts, special effects and pure action, it delivers sensationally.

This mixture of comedy and super-agent spectacle works well at first. But when Schwarzenegger's family and working worlds link up -- an inevitable development -- the plot becomes increasingly ridiculous and overwrought.
True Lies, far too technologically bloated for its cartoony plot, overestimates the human tolerance for high-tech mayhem.
This movie symbolises everything that is wrong with the film industry.
I highly, highly, highly reccomend this incredible action pic to anyone who's tired of the same boring Eraser-esque action flick.
Once you get past the stunning special effects and the mind-numbing stuntwork, there's not all that much there.
An incredible show!
Despite some frustrating flaws, the thrills, spills and laughs are there.
The episodes range from farce to pathos, though the dominant tone is one of strained sentimentality.
French New Wave cinema at its high tide.
This is Chabrol's second film, and its subtle development of character points toward the dense structures of his later films with their reluctance either to condemn or extol without reservation.
The masterpiece of Kenji Mizoguchi's prewar period.
The premise of North sounds flat, the previews look insipid, and, while the movie doesn't turn out nearly as bad as either would lead you to believe, North is still a lackluster production.
I hated this movie. Hated hated hated hated hated this movie. Hated it.
North seldom raises more than a chuckle.
This movie is aimed at neither kids nor adults; it simply isn't aimed.
A witless exercise in adult-bashing.

Young kids will likely enjoy watching all the hubbub the gutsy protagonist stirs up and identify with his plight, but most anyone over the age of 14 will find the film alternately too cute for its own good and too blind to quit while it's ahead.
Elijah Wood has fast become the most appealing young actor making movies today, turning in consistently solid performances in a variety of roles.
It's strange and oddly distasteful, at its best managing to be bad in some original and unexpected ways.
Renaissance Man is a labored, unconvincing comedy that seems cobbled together out of the half-understood remnants of its betters.

As strange as it sounds, DeVito's performance is about the only aspect of the film that isn't wholly fraudulent, if only because his typical feisty abrasiveness protects him from sinking to the level of Marshall's mawkishness.
But this is not brilliant emotional manipulation. It's just the same sort of audience pandering Marshall picked up from all those years co-starring in "Laverne and Shirley."

Ciao Professore is a sweet movie with some lovable characters in it, but there was a time when Wertmuller would have snorted in scorn at the simplicity of this material, and gone to work to make it her own.
As a comedy, The Mask is genial, but its recycled plot is far too thin for the film to succeed as either an adventure or a spoof.

The Mask is a perfect vehicle for the talents of Jim Carrey, who underwhelmed me with Ace Ventura, Pet Detective but here seems to have found a story and character that work together with manic energy.

Even without the state-of-the-art, boundary-busting computerized effects from Industrial Light & Magic, Carrey's a human cartoon, and his spontaneous, Avery-esque, anything-for-a-laugh outrageousness makes this otherwise blank Mask a must-see.
Doesn't have any more material than a Tex Avery cartoon.
A highly imaginative film.
Carrey has yet to find the perfect vehicle for himself, but The Mask, while hardly as fantastic as it should have been, is a step in the right direction.
A wacky and eye-popping (literally) combination of live-action comedy and computer animation.
You cannot know the history of silent film unless you know the face of Renee Maria Falconetti.
Sit down with an open heart and an open mind, and you'll be blown away. This is the reason they make movies.
Falconetti burns (no pun intended) as the tortured young woman -- if only the rest of the movie could keep up with her and the cinematography.
The chief reason for its legendary reputation is the brilliant match between its timeless historical subject ... and Dreyer's decision to film it primarily in relentless close-ups.
Perhaps one of the most intricate and powerful achievements of the silent era.
This is one of the most memorable films ever made.

There are images of astonishing beauty in Godfrey Reggio's Powaqqatsi, sequences when we marvel at the sights of the Earth, and yet when the film is over there is the feeling that we are still waiting for it to begin.
Monster movies are supposed to frighten the audience; this one fails utterly in that arena.
An effective attempt to place a werewolf story in an incongruous setting, with the closely observed details of that setting used to make the story seem more believable.
A sometimes shaky, always enchanting Beauty and the Beast story for grown-ups that is the very essence of smart fun -- droll, sophisticated and surprisingly, pleasingly light.
Nichols has allowed Wolf to evolve from a well-mounted, supernatural drama to goofy camp.

What makes Nicholson’s performance effective in the early scenes, when the noble Will struggles to keep a lid on his new savagery, also zaps any suspense — we know he won’t hurt Laura or anyone else who doesn’t have it coming.
Nichols tries mightily to put a new spin on a very old tale, but try as he might, he never gets much off the ground.
An excellent movie directed by Mike Nichols.
Most of the way, Wolf is quite satisfying, and Nicholson is in top form.
It's a wonderfully entertaining and beautifully performed film.
The true measure of a star is his ability to transform ordinary material into movie magic. James Stewart's presence in this routine crime-drama gives a plain film a complex core.
Bohringer makes the character real in countless details, and Laura's confusion and vulnerability undermine Collard's theme.
The setup promises something more invigorating than it delivers.
If you respond to film noir, if you like dark streets and women with scarlet lips and big fast cars with running boards, the look of this movie will work some kind of magic.
Most of the time, you won't be chuckling, so much as contemplating the emptiness that lies in the brains of all too many production executives.
Overproduced but underwhelming monolith.
The ups and downs of this movie are similar to those of the Batman films, and most audiences may be as forgiving of them here as there.
The movie, from start to finish, is just an exercise in style.
A decidedly mixed bag of campy humor, wild-eyed fantasy and high-tech special effects.
It's an efficient, entertaining atrocity.
Witty and beautifully drawn.
There clearly has been a conscious effort to please adults as much as children. Happily, for those of us who generally stay far away from 'cartoons,' they have succeeded.
A superbly drawn animated feature.
An ingenious mixture of themes from narrative sources as ancient and varied as Hamlet, the Old Testament and The Odyssey.
An impressive, almost daunting achievement.
In the end, it's a thumping good adventure in a far-away land, a whole greater than the sum of its parts.
Technically an amazing and dazzling movie.
The entire film is loaded with eye-popping visuals, which, even on a second viewing, never fail to mesmerize.
One of Disney's greatest achievements.
It's all calculated to be wonderfully entertaining and almost every frame hits the mark.
Winning and gorgeous.

Stone...doesn't know the meaning of moderation or subtlety, and opts instead for something that is excessive and self-indulgent. It's as if he wants to shout out the statement: 'Look at what I can do! I'm an artist!'
Seeing this movie once is not enough. The first time is for the visceral experience, the second time is for the meaning.
The main problem with Killers...is that it degenerates into the very thing it criticizes.
Welcome to Natural Born Killers, Stone's empty, manic meditation on society's glorification of violence and the ugly heroes it loves to hate.

Berserk from the outset, Natural Born Killers lunges for our collective viscera in its opening sequence (surely one of the most brilliant establishing sequences of all time) and never lets go for the next two hours.

Don't miss this and it's brilliance on so many different levels; film making, acting, directing, editing, soundtrack and of course the whole twisted backbone of the thing -- Quentin Tarantino's script.
Stone's attempt to break new ground with stylized visuals, MTV editing and a story that combines parody and satire, is more annoying than enlightening.
NBK brilliantly leaves the attentive viewer with more questions as to whether they're part of the solution or the problem itself.
Perhaps the most unjustly neglected of Luchino Visconti's early films is this hilarious 1951 comedy.
Ichikawa has always been a difficult director to pin down. His work here seems to inhabit a static, novelistic space, but the final result is personal and elegantly filled out.
Left me silent and wide-eyed.
A tumultuous riot of inspired filmmaking.
The astonishing hook-and-ladder battle alone is worth the ticket price.
As Buuel's most directly political work, it certainly warrants a look.
Buuel's apparent lack of compassion for his juvenile delinquents is what finally makes the film an unusually powerful social document and a disturbing piece of drama.
If you're looking for a late summer, "feel good" romantic comedy, there aren't too many around more affable than this one.
Bergman never goes for heavy-handed schmaltz, and the whole movie has the same lighthearted big city spirit as the New York Post headlines that follow the story.
Simply and without pandering or insults to your intelligence, the movie delivers more of the old-style pleasures of moviegoing than any other picture in a long while.
In the end, It Could Happen to You is a lot like the cop and the waitress: sweet, naive, not too smart, but likable.
The warmth and graciousness apparent in every frame keep this movie touching and sweet.
The movie starts wonderfully, ends great, and has perfect pacing throughout.
A steady stream of laughs and terrific chemistry between Cage and Fonda, bolstering both the comedy and the ultimate romance.
The nastiness in the movie feels derived from life, while all the niceness feels canned -- imported from old Jimmy Stewart pictures.
Good but flawed.
Passionate and magical, Forrest Gump is a tonic for the weary of spirit.
What a magical movie.
This is one summer movie that doesn't evaporate the minute you leave the theater.
Hanks is superb, reemploying the childlike presence he brought to Big.
Forrest Gump has an intricacy and depth that is more rewarding while still being enormously engaging.
The worst thing is the film goes for brilliance when it really isn't.
Both dark and sweet.
It was almost like it was written by a committee and everybody got to write 10 minutes of the story.
It's been awhile since we've had a movie that offered so much and generally managed to deliver on all counts.
It sure seemed great at the time, but Gump is aging, and not very well.
It could be said that Forrest Gump is the definitive American movie.
Hanks is so charming as Gump, so heroic in his guilelessness and belief in simple virtues, that you want to excuse the film's excesses and overlook Zemeckis' weakness for easy, maudlin sentiment.
Like the best movie actors, Hanks is a superb reactor.

Working in two platoons, [the four screenwriters] have skillfully removed all vestiges of originality from this story, and turned in a perfectly-honed retread of every other movie about how a team of losers wins the big game.
Naive and ragged by ordinary standards, but a lot of life breaks in where formalism breaks down.
It's been a long time since there's been a good baseball movie. The Scout makes you wonder if there's ever going to be one again.
Rarely does a movie start high and go downhill so fast. It's as if the filmmakers progressively lost their nerve with every additional scene.
A genuine -- and immensely enjoyable -- curiosity.
The Scout proves to be an unsatisfying single that should have been a home run.
What is the sound of one hand clapping? The audience giving it up for The Next Karate Kid.
It's a decent enough entry into the Karate Kid series, if you don't mind having seen it all done before, and better.

The film does have a few warm moments and is at its best when simply developing the relationship between Miyagi and Julie. But, as you might expect, those moments are few and far between and overshadowed by all the ludicrous plotting.

Corrina, Corrina has its heart in the right place, and its characters are some of the nicest people I've met at the movies lately, but the movie seems to exist under a cloud of gloom, and I kept hoping for sunshine.
The screenplay, work by five writers, based on a story by three others, seems to have been rewritten often enough that any individuality has been lost.
Every promising situation -- Shore suffering through basic training, dealing with real battle and so on -- suffers immediate creative fatigue.
It's a tale as old as the jokes, which were already old when the Peloponnesians went to war.
Let's put it this way: it's a 90-minute comedy, and I laughed just once (the guy in front of me spilled popcorn on his whiny date, if you must know).
For the uninitiated, Shore's screen persona is somewhere between Jim Varney and Jim Carrey -- if you drained them of all their energy and personality.
With a script as smart as the title character, Fresh keeps its viewers guessing.

Here's a movie filled with drama and excitement, unfolding a plot of brilliant complexity, in which the central character is solemn and silent, saying only what he has to say, revealing himself only strategically.
Yakin may be a novice, but from the movie's first poetic images, this gifted young filmmaker tells his story with a sure, distinctly personal voice.

[Fresh] is urgently lyrical, right down to its final, haunting image. And in lead performer Sean Nelson, first-time filmmaker Yakin has a 12-year-old breath of fresh air whose beatific face could launch a thousand scripts.
It takes a bit to get going, but once it does, Fresh never lets up.
Perhaps in not forming into a story, the movie does a service, by not forcing a conclusion where none should exist.
Though the picture doesn't build from scene to scene, that doesn't matter: Each segment on its own is richly detailed and vivid.

[Anders is] Anglo-American, and yet the flavor, the rhythm, the slang and the visual detail that she captures feel authentic -- to this viewer, anyway -- as though she were an insider telling her story from experience.

This plot, and the attitudes that underlie it, remind me of the patronizing tone of novels set in Africa 50 years ago, about colorful colonials and backward natives. The movie is not overtly racist. But there is an unpleasant undertone.

Possibly the most radical of the blaxploitation films of the 70s, this movie was an overnight success when released in 1973, then was abruptly taken out of distribution for reasons still not entirely clear.
Some movies just don't know when enough is enough.
I don't want to spoil it for you, but let's just say the gangster doesn't get what he wants, and true love saves the day.
Question: Will Hollywood ever retire the Hooker With a Heart of Gold?
A preposterous movie about a boy, a babe and a car, all of them functioning minimally in what is essentially a showcase for Melanie Griffith's body.
Sour is not the word for it. The milk obtained from this money is positively rancid.
It can not make up its mind if it is a movie for the early teen set or its target audience is grownups.
Ridiculous, tasteless, offensive and unfunny, Milk Money was the perfect final film to see in this string of losers. It made all the others seem better.
The result is not an especially good movie, but it has a surprising number of good parts to it -- moments that have a life of their own.
Sometimes funny, sometimes painful, but most often solipsistic.
Time paradoxes are supposed to be mind-boggling; Timecop has reduced them to a level somewhere between confusing and dumb.
Timecop, a low-rent Terminator, is the kind of movie that is best not thought about at all, for that way madness lies.
In spite of its glitches, Timecop is lots of fun, a blast from the past.
Good dumb fun.

Some impressive Terminator-type special effects, various plot holes, kung-fu derring-do and action as well as some wooden acting by the muscles from Brussels make for Saturday matinee entertainment, but little else.
Being a time-travel epic, plot holes abound here, but it's Van Damme's cute little attempt at being the family man that ruins that oh-so-necessary willing suspension of disbelief.
In terms of plot and direction, there are loopholes galore and too much in-your-face audience-pummeling for my taste.
A satisfying science-fiction thriller.
It's not some little plot-bound genre formula. It's invigorating, how much confidence it has, and how much space it allows itself.
Convincing and heartbreakingly tragic.
Overcooked and half-baked.
This film is the distillation of an intriguing blend of romantic comedy, satire, drama, and philosophy.
It appears at first to be about the casual lives of young men trying to launch their careers, but eventually ... it reveals darker depths and meanings.
Stillman pulls confident, polished performances from all his actors.
Narratively, Barcelona gives itself nowhere to go.
What is right with this movie is the directing and the script.
This isn't for everyone, to be sure, but those who enjoy literate, witty movies over shoot-'em-up, blow-'em-up fare should find much to savor.
Ted and Fred may finally leave you not caring about Stillman's protagonists -- not so much ugly Americans as mildly unpleasant Americans.
[The filmmakers] discover no great answers or revelations, but by the end of the film they, and we, have a remarkable impression of a life lived curiously, but well.

This fictional documentary's films-in-miniature -- subdued, engaging grace notes that run from 45 seconds to several minutes -- create a subtle, appropriately unconventional portrait of this eccentric man.

The Perils of Pauline (1914), Pathe's silent film episodic serial, is considered the most famous suspense serial in cinema history. It is not the first serial, however -- that honor goes to Edison's What Happened to Mary? (1913).
It may be absurd, and even risible, but its single-minded concentration has its own kind of fascination and power.
The film is overdirected and, paradoxically, underdeveloped, but it does feature some marvelous, dazzling imagery by ace cinematographer George Schneevoight.
Tolkin gives us one richly detailed set piece after another.
You can't stop watching because nobody in the audience, and possibly nobody on the screen, has any idea what's going to happen next.

Imagination is a gift. It bestows power, insight and the ability to dream. It takes courage to dream on a big scale, which is what Emir Kusturica does in Arizona Dream, a wonderfully absurdist comedy...
There is so much to like in Arizona Dream that you can't help wondering why you don't like it better.
The most insightful and deliciously droll look at show business since Robert Altman skewered Hollywood in 1992's The Player.
The movie is very funny and, in the way it follows its logic wherever it leads, surprisingly tough.
As one-liningly sharp and self-deprecating as you'd expect. If not more so.
Has more laughs packed into its exquisitely orchestrated 99 minutes than anything [Allen's] done in nearly 20 years.
The most substantive, accessible -- not to mention the funniest -- film that the prolific writer-director has made in years.
Buzzes with classic one-liners, bright performances and off-the-cuff contemplations about love, art and death.
An honest attempt at creating farce, albeit one that tweaks the age-old artist's dilemma throughout.
I give it a mild thumbs up -- I had hoped for more, but it is funny.
Most of the way this one is a riot, the comedy that Allen fans have been waiting for.
Woody Allen at his best -- a gem of a Broadway fable with a crafty premise, a raft of brilliant actors at the top of their form and a bouncy, just-for-pleasure attitude.
It's sweet, likable and even vaguely hip.
Innocent fun and should appeal to the pre-teen audience.

This movie is fascinating in so many different ways: As the story of an extraordinary life, as the reconstruction of the career of one of the greatest of film artists, as the record of an ideological debate, as a portrait of an amazing old woman.
Overly long, but fascinating.
Highly recommended.
... really experience her energy and her drive for cinematic perfection.
However misdirected, Riefenstahl's talent is here in full bloom. And audience members may leave with their own contradictory feelings about her life and what it means.
An exhaustive portrait of Nazi-era filmmaker Leni Riefenstahl.
Ultimately more interesting than satisfying.
The baseball action isn't very interesting because the angels (led by Christopher Lloyd) manipulate the outcomes. And the human interest stuff is canned and unconvincing.
By the time the last out is called, the movie's shamelessness far outweighs its charms. Aimed at the minors, it's in a bush league all its own.

A family-oriented heartstring-yanker so syrupy-sweet in its depictions of the game, angels, orphans, children's wishes, and estranged parents, that it may be all you can do to keep from taking a Louisville Slugger to the projectionist.
The main problem here is one that seems to plague too many movies these days -- the film simply cannot seem to settle on a tone, wildly careening from broad, silly slapstick to syrupy sentiment.
The Navigator looks and feels like it could be one of today's summer mega-blockbusters.
It belongs with Pickpocket and Au hasard Balthazar at the highest level of Bresson's achievement.
This movie is excruciatingly dumb.
The Specialist is one of those films that forces the characters through torturous mazes of dialogue and action, to explain a plot that is so unlikely it's not worth the effort.
With all the preening, posing and stretching, it's hard to know if The Specialist is an action movie or an exercise video.
Llosa relies on stock action shots and tedious exposition to get from scene to scene. You keep waiting for something -- anything -- neat to happen, but nothing does.
A bizarre mix of explosions, histrionic acting and ridiculous plotting ... and it isn't pretty.
Caro Diario is like a sketchbook that shows us what its creator saw, but not always what he thought.

If you're squeamish you should avoid this like the plague; others may find it hard to shake off the artistry and originality of this visionary effort. And if you're looking to be freaked out you shouldn't pass it up.
Ernst Lubitsch seems to be resting on his cliches in this atypically inelegant 1938 comedy.
It's too bad that the requirements of plotting require movies like this to crank up the event count, when actually what works is just the daily minutiae of Bernadette's life.
Those who find men in feathers inherently divine will have a high old time here, and there are enough hilarious cinematic moments for the gob-smacked rest.
The year's one clear candidate for future cult status.
It's a cute trio... But like the tour bus, the movie suffers engine failure after a while.
Writer-director Stephan Elliott is obviously fond of his characters, and this may account for the upbeat story line, but it blinds him to how very annoying two hours of dishing can be.
This is a road movie with a difference.
Unpredictable, adventurous and entertaining, Priscilla is that wonderful thing in showbiz, a unique work entirely of its own creation, but informed by the culture from whence it has erupted.
You may have Gloria Gaynor's 'I Will Survive' rattling through your head for a few days, but that's a small price to pay for an audience with true royalty.
Outrageous, in a calculated way, the film's success relies heavily on the players, and fortunately, Stamp, Weaving and Pearce are up for it.
For sheer camp value, Priscilla is a lot of fun, even if it has next to nothing to say.
Bernadette -- formerly Ralph -- turns out to be an excellent role for Stamp.
Blue Sky is such an ungainly mixture of politics, emotion and nostalgia that it's a wonder the movie works at all - but it does.
Even without that lumpy subplot, Blue Sky is wildly uneven and is virtually held together most of the way by the performances of its stars.
Ingmar Bergman's days behind the camera may be over, but he apparently still has a worthwhile story or two left to tell.

There's little here you haven't seen in other artists' summer reminiscences. But there's something delicate and magical about this particular season, probably because of the knowledge that you are tapping directly into Bergman's childhood.
A good movie.

If the story seems a little waterlogged, it's still big, loud, and fun to watch.
Just another special effects-laden, digitally enhanced, B-movie, adventure thriller.
Costner and Hopper give good characterizations. The entire movie, unfortunately, doesn't quite deliver the punch it ought to.
Although the show grew on me, it is too ridiculous for me to recommend it.
Waterworld is a near-model summer fantasy: two hours and 21 minutes of loud, expansive fun.

Waterworld is the movie that didn't happen. Which is a roundabout way of saying that the infamous Universal film is very good, damn good -- not great, mind you, but rousing and continually entertaining.
There is the nagging feeling that much of the film's story, dialogue and character development were left on the cutting-room floor.
Has the makings of a cult movie.
Waterworld is a marginal film: always extravagant, sometimes entertaining, often preachy and dull -- a pure formula picture.
Waterworld is ugly, loud, stupefyingly absurd.
The Usual Suspects is an accomplished synthesis of noir elements and, as such, is an entertaining entry to the genre.
Once again, my comprehension began to slip, and finally I wrote down: 'To the degree that I do understand, I don't care.'

Certain 'big twists' may have hogged the limelight of late, but rarely have they come 'bigger' or better than in Bryan Singer's glorious exercise in taut intrigue, dazzling plotting and criminal psychology.
Lots of fun and a very handsome, widescreen production by director Bryan Singer, who co-wrote the original script with once-and-future partner (and ex-private detective) Christopher McQuarrie.

Next to the steady diet of Hollywood formula, contrived plots and situations a regular moviegoer can spot a mile off, The Usual Suspects is something quite different: A movie that's smarter than you are.

After I first saw the film, I recommended it to people as an entertaining and commercial crime thriller; a standard story done very well. And then I saw it again. The movie is so much better the second time.
The twist at the end is a corker, but crucial questions remain unanswered. What's interesting, though, is how little this intrudes on our enjoyment.
After following the beckoning twists and turns, you're left trapped and more than a little disappointed for getting in so deep.
The only usual thing about The Usual Suspects is the title. All else is a fun, fresh, gritty new take on something you thought was old and familiar.
There are plenty of twists in the plot to keep you on your toes throughout the film.

In the press notes for The Usual Suspects, the director speculates that viewers will enjoy his film even more the second time. That's because you need a scorecard to keep track of this thriller the first time around.
The Usual Suspects is a movie with style to burn, and, initially, that is this crime drama's most mesmerizing aspect.
Nothing is what it seems in this layered, velvety movie (which was shot in handsome wide-screen format) -- the truth keeps shifting -- and nothing matters either.
The interaction of all the characters is both fascinating and unusual.
The Usual Suspects is a knockout suspense yarn with so many twists and turns you're never quite sure where it's going to wind up. And the trip is enormously satisfying.
Director Bryan Singer gives his film enough surface flash to entertain future late-night cable possibilities.
All the actors nail their parts with ultra-cool finesse, and just listening to Del Toro mumble his lines is worth the cost of the ticket alone. Singer's direction is also completely on target.

Director Bryan Singer works so hard at evoking an air of world-weary fatalism that it's a shame to find out, at the end, that the little things -- like characters and story -- don't matter as much as the oh-so-clever denouement.
As entertainment, the film is a lukewarm experience. But as a piece of construction, The Usual Suspects is a slick bit of business.
Most of the time I hardly knew what was going on, but I couldn't wait to see what happened next.
It isn't as good as the original Under Siege, but it moves quickly, has great stunts and special effects, and is a lot of fun.
For the most part, the characters are richly drawn, and this helps to maintain balance among the different stories.
The film's director, Gurinder Chadha, uses the day trip as a way to look at issues in the British Asian community, where old traditions and new ways make for uncomfortable situations.
In the end... the world explored here is fresh terrain for the movies, and the background of the characters unique, the characters themselves seem all too familiar.
Although Chadha's compassion for her characters is fully evident, she tethers them to the story plot lines. To pay more vivid tribute to her Asian milieu, she has a lot of stylistic unraveling to do.
It is of the here and now, of daily grinds and necessary escapes. It's a welcome break from our own routines, a getaway into a lyrical, uncommon world.

Overplotted and somewhat confusing in its first third, "Bhaji at the Beach" nonetheless manages to overcome its narrative weaknesses and develops into an engrossing character study almost in spite of itself.
The film is played out as social- commentary comedy, steeped in serious issues.
Martha and Ethel is as fascinating for what it doesn't say as for what it does.
Given Washington's presence and the promise of a virtual reality action story, Virtuosity has some appeal -- provided, of course, the viewers aren't selective.
Virtuosity is an example of a struggle that goes on in Hollywood between formula and invention.
The world of Virtuosity may be spanking new, but the ideas are yesterday's news.
Make no mistake about it, Brett Leonard's Virtuosity seems like a less-filling nouvelle dish full of sci-fi action. But what it really is, is 100% all beef.
Disappointing action movie which doesn't ever fully exploit the possibilities of its premise.
Lots of techno buzzwords aside, there is not much new to this affair and one rather hopes that Leonard could have done something more original with the material at hand.
Virtuosity is 95 minutes of unsubstantial firefights and meandering plot twists.
There are some interesting ideas at work here, with potential for commentary on news vs. entertainment and violence in America. But it remains unexplored.
Someone should tell Hollywood that the mass-killer genre is dead and that its virtual reality counterpart is already wheezing.
It takes a while to get rolling, and the early character development is weak, but pretty soon, everyone's caught up in this innovative take on the cat and mouse game.
There's a tiredness to its action sequences and a dullness about its plotting that no amount of special-effects legerdemain can hide.
Nine Months is one of those movies where the outcome is abundantly clear to everyone but the hero, who remains in the hapless position of playing dumb because, if he didn't, there wouldn't be a plot.
Kids shows what transpires when children are set adrift in a heartless world, and warns us what happens -- and is already happening -- in the absence of love and guidance.
Kids is the kind of movie that needs to be talked about afterward.
Ostensibly about the banality of youthful evil, Kids is simply about its own banality.
Kids, a disturbingly voyeuristic look at adolescent promiscuity, is virtually child pornography disguised as a cautionary documentary.
No matter the interpretation, the film's sensationalism is eerily frank no matter if it's presented in good taste or not.
Kids doesn't let itself or us off the hook; we're all responsible for what we see. And what we won't see.
Kids is an emotional sucker punch, a raw, dirty, disturbing piece of cinma vrit filmmaking that simultaneously hooks and repulses you from its opening scenes.
The script and especially the low quality of the acting makes you think you are watching a poor documentary of an extremely important subject.

A movie that pretends to be concerned with making an important social statement about modern youth, but which instead is just relentlessly in-your-face, wallowing in degradation to make a quick, controversial buck at the local multiplex.
Deeply shocking and disturbing, this film's hype exists for a reason.
With his debut feature, Larry Clark has made an unpleasant film about a few repulsive characters who lead a fairly irredeemable existence.
Clark has stepped back into objectivity so far that he has neglected his role as interpreter for us.
Elocuente seal de alarma de lo que tenemos que brindarles a las nuevas generaciones: direccin, educacin sexual y motivacin
If nothing else, Rudnick and director Christopher Ashley know how to keep the audience off balance and in stitches.
It's more a series of sketches and momentary inspirations than a story that grows interesting.
Warm and witty, but short on stamina.
While this may sound intriguing, the picture merely jumps around clumsily from incident to incident.
A clever, biting and funny movie about gay love in the age of AIDS.
It comes with a superficially sunny sitcom adorableness that ... mixes well with Rudnick's smart, scathing, urban and very dark one-liners.
Some of this is amusing but most simply isn't funny enough to support off-the-wall antics laced with poignancy.
It is startling that such a funny play is not so funny a movie.
A charming, proudly old-fashioned screwball comedy.
The movie is still as hard to follow as The Usual Suspects, and without meaning to be.
A high point of the show, even if it does go on a bit too long, is one great car chase scene.
The result is kind of a mess, but an intriguing one; it's not a very good movie, but you don't stop watching it.
Having made the splendidly entertaining Cinema Paradiso in 1988, Giuseppe Tornatore now exhibits his versatility with A Pure Formality, which is not entertaining at all.
Bloated and overlong.
What happens looks terrific. Now if [Rodriguez] can harness that technical facility to a screenplay that's more story than setup, he might really have something.
It's big, it's daft, but Desperado is confident and hugely entertaining filmmaking.
In this movie, words and actions speak equally loudly.
On the whole, watching the film is about as much fun as sitting on a cactus.
It's violence as a dance.
A wonderfully exciting and hypnotic action film.
There's plenty of action and will keep Banderas fans happy, but somehow lacks the charm of the original.
A bust-a-gut film experience that reveals Rodriguez as both a stylist versed in the mechanics of popular storytelling and a maverick whose ingenuity guides him along a singular path.
Around the halfway or two-thirds mark, the bloody killings become far too redundant, the best supporting characters are gone and Rodriguez rapidly runs out of fresh ideas.
Desperado, which is nothing but set pieces, snoozes between its scenes of carnage.

As movies go, Desperado is a great big assault weapon with the trigger squeezed hard. It's effective, but it crosses a line -- there's only so much of the same old rat-a-tat-a-tat that you can really take.
On the one hand, Rodriguez sticks with what he knows -- screwball action-adventure. On the other hand, he seems to have shot the same movie twice.
There's nothing like going into a movie with high expectations and coming out in awe....What (Rodriguez) can do with $7 million would make big-budget action directors cry.
Double Happiness is not a deep or brilliant film, but that's not its purpose. It establishes a chatty, confiding tone right at the top and follows through, like a long letter from a good friend.

Hip. Cool. New Wave. Chic. These are only some of the adjectives applicable to Michael Almereyda's new take on the vampire legend. Of course, one other term springs to mind, but it isn't nearly as complimentary. Pretentious.
It's the kind of movie that deals with unspeakable subjects while keeping a certain ironic distance, and using dialogue that seems funny, although the characters never seem in on the joke.
Michael Almereyda's insanely brilliant fantasia on the Dracula legend.
Even as Nadja descends deeper into its downward, surrealistic spiral, the movie's always great to watch.
The most compelling point here has to do with Lowensohn: She's sulky and sad, but her precision is also remarkably vibrant against her shades-of-grey backdrop.
[A] genuinely affecting comedy-horror film that updates the Dracula lineage to present-day New York City.
The film stumbles with hackneyed plotting, uneven performances and a deadly-dull centerpiece that goes on forever.
What could have been a brilliant short becomes deadly, stretched to feature length.
An excellent examination of caste discrimination, human suffering, and the role of women in India's changing culture.
Seema Biswas is convincing in the role: small, fierce, dark-eyed and indomitable.
At the center of the movie are two fine actresses who make Phoolan's unsettled character seem inevitable.
This film's a relentless right hook.
A towering achievement.
To watch the film -- directed with eye-opening vigor by Shekhar Kapur -- is to vicariously experience the social horrors of India's patriarchal system.
This powerful but grueling Indian film is not only a tribute to her spirit, but also a searing indictment of a culture corrupted by the caste system and degraded by chauvinism.
It is representative of a thousand other real-life stories -- albeit not as spectacular as the Devi saga -- which have emerged in the news from India in the past decade.
It is one well worth the time of fans of serious drama.
A fascinating work.
Devi is played by Seema Biswas as a fireball of unrelenting, white-hot fury -- a slap in the face to her country and its barbaric, outdated treatment of women.

Seema Biswas, who plays the protagonist, conveys a remarkable range of suffering - bleeding, at its extremes, into a kind of pure, white-hot hate that makes the anger of Thelma and Louise look like playground stuff.
An exciting movie that brings Devi's story to life with passion but without passing judgment.
A rare film, one that is intelligent, emotional and exciting.
Besides being an intelligent and gripping thriller with a solid grounding in real, recent historical events, Beyond Rangoon also gives movie-goers a rare opportunity to watch a female hero.
Because the film is well acted and directed, and the Malaysian locations are exotic and seductive, I got involved even though the story ... was so clearly concocted.
An odd movie, brilliant in places, but frustrating all the same.
Get rid of Arquette and this might have been a real movie.
Arquette's central character makes several rather stupid decisions along the way, but the drama of the political events unfolding around her compensates for it.
It's fascinating and rewarding to watch [Arquette] evolve, with much credibility, from her own personal state of immaturity to a state of full growth.
Seems less about the horror suffered by the Burmese than the inconvenience suffered by an American tourist who has lost her passport.

Absolutely typical of the way Hollywood can take a compelling story, full of genuine characters and heartfelt emotion, then hack it to tiny bits and put it back together, Frankenstein-like, into a sappy, overwrought drama.
Boorman's metaphysical musings might work if he integrated them more fully into his film, instead of making them secondary to action sequences.
It's as if a civil war had been concocted just to take Laura (Patricia Arquette) outside of her not-unjustified misery.
So you wanna make a movie? Well, first, you should see "Living in Oblivion," Tom DiCillo's savagely funny satire of the world of independent filmmaking.
"Oblivion" has a surrealistic, guilty-fun quality. It feels almost too good to be true.

DeCillo keeps the film moving with the kind of frantic energy you find on a real film set, alternating between judicious use of black-and-white and garish color, all the while keeping both frazzled director Nick and the audience just a little off balance.
Engaging and bright, witty and smart, Living in Oblivion is a riotous romp through the world of moviemaking, with emphasis on the helplessness one feels on a low-budget set when things go wrong.
A smart, funny send-up of the trials and joys of filming on big egos and low budgets - subjects that writer-director Tom DiCillo and his collaborators presumably know first-hand.
The movie, directed by Chris Noonan, who wrote the screenplay with George Miller, takes a child's-eye view of a world that is photographed to look like a storybook come to life.
Through a mixture of imaginative storytelling, impressive animatronics, and irresistible cuteness, Babe casts a spell over all viewers -- young, old, or somewhere in between.
Babe is a movie made with charm and wit, and unlike some family movies it does not condescend, not for a second.
A hilarious fantasy, about a plucky piglet that learns how to tend sheep, Babe is a barnyard charmer.
The underlying tricks are never allowed to upstage the story in all its humble sweetness.
So bloody loveable that even the worst cynic will be hard-pressed to condemn it.
In the end, the most impressive moments in the film seem to be the technical ones, rather than the storyline.
A charming and ingenious hit.
It's a clever, witty, touching piece of work that, coincidentally enough, is also a decidedly excellent date movie. Really.
It has been so long since I've genuinely cared about movie characters in a lighthearted story like this that I nearly wept with joy.
This is a good family film.
Though the filmmakers romanticize farm life, they don't sugarcoat the realities.
A silk purse among children's entertainment.
That little pig is so darn cute.
The world of Babe isn't a seamless one, but it's surely inviting and rewarding.
It's rare to see this kind of care expended on any movie; on a family picture, it's a small miracle.
Country Life may not be the deepest Vanya I have seen, but it is the funniest, bringing out the play's buried potential for farce as well as tragedy.
The Tie That Binds is an attempt to recapture the spirit of The Hand That Rocks the Cradle, which was itself simply a more sophisticated variation on the slasher genre.
One of the sleaziest movies of the year and certainly the most unpleasant.
What is amazing is how the movie manages to be funny and amusing while tippy-toeing around (a) sex, (b) controversy and (c) any originality in the plot.

Screenwriter Douglas Carter Beane pilfers not just plot elements from "Priscilla," but also stirs in big chunks of "Fried Green Tomatoes," "Bagdad Cafe," "Auntie Mame," "The Music Man" and "Cinderella."
Improbable as this all sounds, "Wong Foo" is a great deal of fun and a small step forward in Hollywood's depiction of homosexuals.
For some, the film's unabashed sentimentality and fairy-tale quality may go too far, but To Wong Foo is such a delight that it's easy to overlook the few awkward moments.
Leguizamo and Swayze - and especially Snipes - just seem like Hollywood stars putting on a cabaret show. There is never any sense that these guys are real people.
It's a glam-o-rama party until the trio hits the road. Suddenly, Wong Foo is all cross-dressed with no place to go -- but down.
Although it borrows heavily from last year's Priscilla: Queen of the Desert, To Wong Foo is still quite a bit different and takes cross-dressing into realms I never knew existed.
The best thing about this movie is all the free advice it offers. As Vida warns before she leaves town, "Believe in yourself, and moisturize - this I cannot stress enough."
Braveheart is a great, ambitious gamble that pays off. In his second film as director, Gibson has come through with an exhilarating new-fashioned epic.
With its clashing armies, heartstopping action, and grand sense of romance, this is the sort of film it's a pleasure to see and review.
An action epic with the spirit of the Hollywood swordplay classics and the grungy ferocity of The Road Warrior.

Braveheart opts to turn cowardly, settling for the magnification of Gibson's idol status, forfeiting the complex, more nebulous magnificence of the real Sir William Wallace and virtually excising the strategic brilliance of Robert The Bruce.
Gibson's raw energy and storytelling power in Braveheart are undeniable. If the film doesn't meet his ambitions, it's because he set the bar so high.
[Gibson] has created a completely adequate modern facsimile of the classic romantic epic.

If Braveheart were any longer, it would have to be moved around by flatbed truck. By the time the story trudges to its hyper-climactic close, you feel as though you marched through a couple of meaningless campaigns.
Mel Gibson's Braveheart is probably not good history, and it's no documentary -- but it sure makes great Hollywood cinema.
Braveheart is history the way it should be told, full of sex and treachery and battle and passion and Mel Gibson in a kilt.
Excellent battle scenes complement this historical epic about one man's quest to free his people.
I continue to enjoy watching and re-watching it, and share much of Mel Gibson's enthusiasm for his project.
A grand cinematic adventure.
The story itself is quite compelling, and the script is excellent.
With a bit of restraint Gibson might have had a great movie here instead of merely a pretty good one.
Though lumpy and even redundant, Braveheart constantly rebounds on some bold note.
A vastly entertaining and powerful film.
As far as a good old-fashioned story of historical oppression goes, it does sweep you up and entertain.
At times the film seems an obsessive ode to Mel Gibson machismo.
Everybody knows that a non-blubbering clause is standard in all movie stars' contracts. Too bad there isn't one banning self-indulgence when they direct.

Copycat doesn't have the dark tones of Seven, or that movie's distinctive look. But in its own way, it is as effective. It creates original characters and makes them more important than the plot. We care, and that's the key.

Amiel... delivers a taut, gripping thriller and, with the help of his accomplished leads, succeeds in camouflaging some of the mammoth holes in Ann Biderman and David Madsen's otherwise intelligent and inventive screenplay.
Has too many characters and needless plot twists -- padding in between corpses.
As its title indicates, it's lacking in imagination, a movie with too few original thoughts in its head.
Copycat, despite two tough-babe leads to kill for, flies in more directions than scattered kitty litter.
For a decent adrenaline rush without the churning stomach, this is the right kind of murder movie.
Moonlight and Valentino is very sincere, very heartfelt and very bad.

Watching Theremin: An Electronic Odyssey is a curious experience. You begin with interest, and then you pass through the stages of curiosity, fascination and disbelief, until in the last 20 minutes, you arrive at a state of dumbfounded wonder.
Dad I not known that this was a documentary, I could have convinced myself that this was a Woody Allen comedy about a genius inventor of screwball machines.
A fine, straight-forward documentary that relates an incredible story.
The film lays meticulous groundwork for a payoff that never takes place. The last 20 minutes, which should deliver a big emotional punch, simply do not work.
Here it is at last, at long last, after years and years and years: A movie where the smart fat kid gets the girl and humiliates the football hero.
"Angus" was directed by Patrick Read Johnson from Jill Gordon's screenplay. They have my condolences.
From the terrific credit sequence to the solid performances to the high-profile soundtrack, Johnson has fashioned an affecting picture with an endearing, unlikely hero.
For a movie that extols the virtues of being different, Angus is a frustratingly ordinary story of a high-school underdog: a chow hound in puppy love.
Here's a sure method to guess whodunnit in bad mystery thrillers: pick the suspect most likely to shock the audience and you have the killer.
[Hall] can't triumph over the problems in the script, or tie up all the loose ends, but his brisk, competent approach does minimize the effects of these flaws.
Borderline ridiculous and ultimately pointless thriller.
One of the least subtle motion pictures this year.
Utterly forgettable.
Even with its sights set this low, the film misfires on every level.
It's mysterious and sexy enough to keep tension alive until, too bad, the whole thing collapses with a twist ending that is nearly laughable.
A Walk in the Clouds is a glorious romantic fantasy, aflame with passion and bittersweet longing.

This is not a "religious" film, and the brothers are far from saints. But they know right and wrong, and in their imperfect ways they are struggling to attain a state of grace. Sometimes they slip. Sometimes they don't struggle so hard. Life's like that.
The movie has too many scenes that work well on their own, but don't add to the final effect.
There are many small moments of perfect observation. But I never really felt they were building to anything, or heading anywhere.
This one really moves and breathes.
Even if the movie could have been better -- deeper and more evocative -- it's pretty good just as it is.
... full of one cliche after another and it's extremely predictable. Overall, the problem in the movie is that it takes itself way too seriously.
There's so little to watch besides Carrey, in fact, it makes you actually miss (gasp!) Sean Young from Ace 1.
[The actors] make this good-hearted little film into a quiet meditation on fate, tact, and poetry.
An extremely slow, but heart warming little picture.
Literary purists will be aghast at some of the liberties taken with the original text, but my complaints have more to do with cinematic misjudgments than with those in the book-to-screen translation.
The movie has removed the character's sense of guilt, and therefore the story's drama.
Picture yourself trudging out of the theater with a letter "D" (for "disappointment") firmly pinned to your chest.
The picture's period furnishings include Hester's 17th-century hot tub.

Roland Joffe's deeply ridiculous movie is caught between rocks and hard places, from its "what were they thinking?" concept ("freely adapted from the novel by Nathaniel Hawthorne") to its muddled execution.
Pitiful loose interpretation of the Nathaniel Hawthorne novel of adultery and its implications.
This catastrophic conglomeration of Puritanical repression and modern sensibilities squanders terrific acting talent and sumptuous production values, not to mention a darn good story.
The result is merely a big-budget, opulently costumed soap opera that is way too long (two hours, 15 minutes) and way too slow.
Students beware: This is no sub for Cliffs Notes. The script takes more liberties with the text than Elizabeth Berkley did with that pole in Showgirls.

With Demi Moore and Gary Oldman as those 17th century adulterers Hester Prynne and the Rev. Dimmesdale, the movie has its silly moments, but more impressively, it is turgid, the second most prevalent trait of Joffe's films, and long, the third.
Unstrung Heroes has been directed by Diane Keaton with an unusual combination of sentiment and quirky eccentricity. There are moments so touching that the heart almost stops.
One of the most remarkable and haunting documentaries ever made.
A masterpiece of neutral ambiguity.
Rarely has there ever been a work as great as Crumb, an achievement resting on both Zwigoff's talent and grace and on the enigma and poetry of its subject.

Crumb's sense of humor is his saving personal grace and the movie's insurance policy against total immersion into the morbid. But just so you know, Crumb fully earns its most revealing screen credit: 'David Lynch Presents.'
Seven is unnecessarily gory and runs for a little too long, but neither of these elements detracts much from the film's enjoyability (unless you have a weak stomach).
Good as it is, it misses greatness by not quite finding the right way to end.
Eventually, with its irrationally downbeat ending, Seven even drags the viewer down into the abyss.
Well worth a look.
Unfortunately, screenwriter Andrew Kevin Walker's finale, in addition to its grossness, feels like an act of treachery against the viewer.
Seven, a grisly social allegory drawn in blood and spawned in despair, casts a lingering, malodorous spell.
We stumbled out of a screening of the new psychological drama Seven gasping for breath, and with a pounding headache and a stomach knotted like a Boy Scout badge test.
Grisly and disturbing, but very, very good.
Along with the camerawork, the sets by Arthur Max were depressingly and shockingly perfect.
dark, brooding, occasioanlly funny, satirical, smart, and entertaining.
When's the last time you saw a movie in which The Divine Comedy figured as a significant plot point?
Positively dripping with a soggy, oppressive atmosphere, the film is blanketed with a miasma of madness.
As the story progresses, the film manages to become quite engrossing, but it is a bit disconcerting that it can be so compelling and repugnant at the same time.
Focus, Freeman and film craft make Seven difficult to dismiss as a stylish exercise, but employing this grisly subject matter for an exercise of any kind is a queasy way to go.
Lean back, peer into the darkness, oh, and hold on to your popcorn and your date exceptionally tight when they get to 'sloth.'
Because the movie believes in its mission, the climax is likely to resonate in your head for hours, perhaps days after viewing.
Hannibal Lecter, say hello to John Doe.
The trouble with Seven is that while the premise is intriguing, the movie is gluey, bumbling and singularly un-thrilling.

Shaky camera shots, dark sets and a disturbing script that takes its characters to the extremes of emotion all contribute to the film creating a unsettled feeling that stays with you for a couple hours after the credits roll.
It is very tiresome peering through the gloom trying to catch a glimpse of something interesting, then having to avert one's eyes when it turns out to be just another brutally tormented body.
Aside from a few effective, low-key scenes, the movie doesn't involve the viewer.

The movie, which is about the Thanksgiving family reunion from hell, is not exactly a comedy and yet not a drama, either. Like many family reunions, it has a little of both elements, and the strong sense that madness is being held just out of sight.
With many of the conversations going on simultaneously, it's difficult -- sometimes even impossible -- to know who is saying what and to whom.
Perhaps the most realistic holiday movie I've ever seen, this oddly charming, poignant, and blackly funny film is a treasure not to be missed.
The film doesn't quite work. The goofball parts just aren't as funny as they're meant to be. But it's enjoyable in stretches, particularly when the zaniness dies down.
Jodie Foster's second film isn't quite that bad, even if it does resort to some we're-all-human humor and a fart joke.
It's likeable in that cosy, wet Sunday afternoon, family sort of way.

There is a good movie contained within Home For the Holidays which I suppose is why most of the critics love this show. For me, there are way too many failed sight gags and characters that got on my nerves with their antics and mannerisms.

There so many likable moments in Home for the Holidays that nail situations so aptly that it's a shame that there are so many more moments that leave you scratching your head and wondering what to think.

Overstuffed with subplots, the film is somewhat episodic in nature, giving each of the characters a few scenes to develop some depth. But their eccentricities seem overly mannered and the big gag scenes are not played strictly for laughs.
With her keen actor's instincts, Foster piles on plenty for her terrific cast to chew on and for us to savor.
This movie is about fixing the little cracks in love, and it's a fine example of the restorer's art.
Holly Hunter is amazing. When watching her you get a sense of her character's whole life, not just the time she spends on the screen.
What's on screen is just a little too familiar to be worth lauding.
I like people who talk interestingly, who have read books, who appreciate verbal wit, who look dubiously at establishment assumptions.
Baumbach makes an assured writing/directing debut, but this will probably do best in the video marketplace.
In general, Baumbach's eye for generational detail is impeccable -- he knows what's on these kids' minds, and has found a language to express it.
Kicking And Screaming's familiarity breeds a caustic but definitive contentment that comes with uncloaking the popular twentysomething trend toward guy-bright-but-lite.
Although Baumbach's film showed a lot of potential, too much was unrealized for me to be able to recommend it.
Stands out amongst the 'twentysomething and fresh out of college' crop of films.
Loses its initial kick and verve and settles down into one long whine.
Writer-director Noel Baumbach establishes an ear for commentary during his wry-guy movie's opening graduation party.
A hilarious example of what not to do when you graduate.
Baumbach fails to realize that too often movies about boring people are, well, boring.

Remember those supermarket contests where the teams raced down the aisles, trying to pile as much stuff as possible into a shopping cart? Steal Big, Steal Little reads like the screenplay was assembled the same way.
Doesn't live up to its promise or premise.
To call this a comedy is a sign of optimism; to call it a comeback for Murphy is a sign of blind faith.
Craven can't keep the comic elements in balance with the horror, and as a result there's no tension or dramatic pull.
This modern fable is little more than a Murphy potboiler, something to while away a couple of hours, rather than fondly remember.
A big, glossy and mostly puerile project bound to please Murphy's fans.
Kadeem Hardison is the best thing about this film, playing Maximillian's slowly rotting ghoul henchman. However; one has to wonder about a film where Eddie Murphy needs comic relief.

They're no match, though, for the crushing disappointment of having to watch Murphy on the comic sidelines. It's like going to a Barbra Streisand concert and being asked to listen with her while the rhythm section sings.
Neither all that scary nor all that hilarious, Vampire in Brooklyn falls directly between the two, into the valley of mediocrity.
Murphy's performance is pretty good most of the way, but he needed a stronger director than horrormeister Wes Craven to keep him in check.
Murphy's pale efforts are enough to make one fondly recall Blacula. Now that was one sucker who knew how to make a film that didn't.
The bottom line is that Vampire in Brooklyn is funny and gross, but saddled with a pedestrian storyline that denies any real magic in its premise and sinks its potential as a dark fantasy.
Lightweight fun.
Symbols are supposed to be subtle, but Rozema is intent upon bludgeoning the audience with them.
When Night is Falling has too many unintended laughs for its passion to be convincing.
A seductive, sensuous experience.
Camille's motivation is a complete mystery to us.
Rozema is a fabulist with a strong visual sense, and she creates a distinctive, enclosed world to illustrate Camille's odyssey.
All the performances are excellent.
The adult actresses are completely superfluous to the movie, which is a contrived Stand by Me kind of story.
It's big, explosive entertainment and, although not directed by Cameron, is very much in the vein we've come to expect from him.
It's fascinating the way Bigelow is able to suggest so much of VR's impact (and dangers) within a movie - a form of VR that's a century old.
Little more than two-and-a-half hours of enjoyable action, futuristic gadgetry and characters perennially on the brink of being compelling.
The early promise of the film gives way to exploitation; satire mutates into drivel.
A successful story of mystery and lost love with a sci-fi twist.
Futuristic film noir mystery with excellent performances and thrilling cinematography.
It's a wildly messed-up, unwieldy, 145-minute movie designed specifically for those audiences who the filmmakers believe haven't been brutalized or quite desensitized enough.
After awhile Strange Days becomes merely a predictable parade of senses-assaulting indignities with a surprisingly conventional, by-the-numbers story.
The end result is an interesting little film that's just, well, 'strange.'
What a kick -- Strange Days is an action movie with real characters and uncommonly skillful actors.
Bigelow is so enamored of high-tech thrills, and so mesmerized by the violence she seeks to condemn, that her efforts at 11th-hour moralizing seem limp and halfhearted.
An ambitious but ultimately disappointing attempt to assemble the latest in fringe-culture byproducts ... into a Hollywood package.
To Die For has its share of truly delicious sequences, and some biting dialogue worth killing for.

Nicole Kidman's work here is inspired. Her clothes, her makeup, her hair, her speech, her manner, even the way she carries herself (as if aware of the eyes of millions) are all brought to a perfect pitch.
Though it may seem less individualistic, less personal than Van Sant's past work, you can feel his sensibility and his talent in every frame.
The delicately featured Phoenix (yes, River's brother) has an extraordinary, chic-oddball presence.
When focused on Suzanne and her fluffy lap dog, the movie is pretty ferocious, but when it turns to the teenagers she seduces, the tone goes a little soft.
Riveting cinema, an engrossing journey into a world where centre stage is the target.
I give To Die For a thumbs up for Kidman's performance, for interesting docudrama style cinematography, and for some huge laughs.
With great wit, humor, and style, this movie serves all America its just desserts and, while the concoction and its ingredients may not kill us, it is to die for.

The result is uneven but often very funny and on-the-mark, with clever observations on our obsession with television, media hype, the influence celebrities have on our culture and even a few bright sight gags.
To Die For endows Nicole Kidman with her career role to date, and one that only an actress with her porcelain features could even attempt.
Director Gus Van Sant can't pull everything together to make any impact at all. It's enough to make you wonder what he's doing with this script in the first place.
Half snappy, sardonic and incisive and half slow-moving, goofy and dense.
From the opening credits, a montage of mass media images from the story we're about to see, the film is saturated with Suzanne's shallow tunnel vision.

It is a pirate picture, pure and simple, and doesn't transcend its genre except perhaps in the luxurious production. Leaner and meaner pirate movies have worked more or less as well, but this one gets the job done.
It takes a two-hour act of will to keep facing the screen during this moribund movie.
It's more like watching a couple of stars play "let's-dress-up-and-be-pirates" rather than accepting them as characters in a swashbuckling adventure.
If the sight of half-naked, tattooed sailors firing cannons at each other shivers your timbers, climb aboard. Even passable pirate movies don't sail by every day.
As long as Errol Flynn stays dead, I don't see any point in making a pirate movie.
It's certainly not a good film, and I can't give it even a lukewarm recommendation, but there are isolated moments when the film works as well for adults as for kids.
One of the problems with the first two-thirds of Magic in the Water is that we don't see Orky. One of the problems with the last third is that we do.
There's definitely something in the water here, but magic...?
Despite these cliches, director and co-screenwriter Rick Stevenson has created some original moments.
If dying of boredom was possible, this movie would be lethal.
While it's amusing for the younger set, an adult outing to Magic in the Water, like my search for Nessie, might benefit from a few shots of magic water en route.

Free Willy and E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial are the obvious inspirations for Magic in the Water, a tepid family fantasy that replaces those child-friendly creatures for a sort of Canadian Loch Ness Monster.
I was so fed up with the bogus sentiment in Magic in the Water that I started wishing it were Harmon gasping for breath instead of the cheap rubber thing with the eyes. No such luck.
You can probably see this movie without doing any major damage, but you and yours will have much more fun reading together from the collected works of Dr. Seuss.
People of any color can sympathize with the plight of Anthony Curtis and understand, if not agree with, the eventual choices life forces him to make.
Here is a film that feels incomplete, as if its last step is into thin air. Scene by scene you feel its skill, but you leave the theater wondering about the meaning of it all.
Dead Presidents is like a shotgun blast in the face: It's that powerful, that lethal, that ugly.
Unfortunately, the story manages to be intense (and very bloody), heartfelt and superficial, all at the same time.
A film that is both tightly focused -- on one man's experience in Vietnam and the South Bronx in the late '60s and early '70s -- and broadly resonant.
The movie makes its point, and continues to hit you over the head with it.
The Hughes Brothers' ambition is admirable, but, as with their main character, ambition gets the better of them.

The level of exaggerated violence and gore is so gross and disgusting that the film takes on a horror-movie look, which tends to undermine its intentions as a thoughtful exploration of troubled times for blacks.
Messy but mesmerizing.
Tate gives a strong performance as Anthony but much of this movie unfolds predictably -- the kind of action you've seen a hundred times in movies before and a thousand times on television.
A Month by the Lake is a sly romantic comedy about a collision of sex, ego, will and pride, all peeping out from beneath great thick layers of British reticence.
Vanessa Redgrave has never been more likable on screen than in her buoyantly athletic turn here.
Worthwhile
My problem with the film was that none of the characters is really interesting.
an extraordinarily difficult to follow film, full of talky, dull melodrama and the glamorization of "proper" 19th century sensibilities
Powder has all of the elements of a successful fantasy, and none of the insights. It's a movie where intriguing ideas lie there on the screen, jumbled and unrealized.
Performed to the hilt by Flanery and filmed with conviction by Victor Salva, the movie is finally too solemn to survive its pushy musical strings.
This is the kind of movie where the filmmaker hopes to shock you with sickening carnage and violent amorality, while at the same time holding himself carefully aloof from it with his style.
You sense that there is so much more at stake here than meets the eye, an extraordinary anger about and fear of 90s purposelessness and predatory intolerance.
More like Natural Born Killers than any other film that comes to mind, but it's ultimately sexier, funnier, and much more 'alternative' (in every sense of the word).
A senseless comic exercise in pushing the limits of decency for that sake alone.
An arty atrocity for thugs and sub-literates that makes Natural Born Killers look like The Sound of Music.
The violence becomes commonplace. The crudities never end. But there are hip benefits for staying to watch.
After seeing all the mayhem and watching how retarded and alienated the teens acted, the film felt as healthy as a combined diet of junk food and crystal meth (speed).
It's young, it's hip, it's excruciating for anyone who has already survived adolescence.
As a stylish black comedy, it is impressively uncompromising and should be applauded.
A note to Gregg: grow up. Really. Move out of your parent's basement, read something other than Salinger, and get a day job.
Admittedly, Araki's new feature may not appeal to all tastes, but that does not at all diminish its immediacy and wit.
In terms of filmmaking, point of view and oddball sense of humor, Araki's film is better than both [Kids and Natural Born Killers].
Hands-down one of the most horrid examples of filmmaking I've seen in ages.
Amy's a screaming, speed-addled banshee, and not the sort of chick you'd want to run into late at night (or spend 85 minutes with in a darkened theater).
Plenty of films have dealt with teen isolation and many more will pile on the shocks, but few have a script this hilarious or a visual sensibility this developed.
Not every kid may be as mad and morose as Araki's lost boys... But a lot are, and in this fevered fantasy of Armageddon, he's got their number.
A joyless lump.
There isn't much of a story in White Man's Burden.
No one looking for an action movie is going to choose this one. Equally obviously, no one interested in a film about racial stereotyping in America wants to sit through chase scenes.
It's undeniably fascinating to watch this hypothetical experiment for a while. But White Man's Burden starts to feel like an only-passable Twilight Zone episode stretched into a full-length movie.
A ham-fisted, under-imagined dialectic on race relations.
You can see the ideas behind White Man's Burden -- they just don't make it to the screen.
A 'what-if' racial story that doesn't pack a punch.
So simple, so broad are White Man's Burden's paint strokes ... that no real lesson outside of the obviously mundane can be elicited, and that's a real shame.
Surprisingly lively and entertaining.
A frustrating film with interesting ideas that never quite come together.
