Watching this movie is like watching Godfrey Cambridge's racial switcheroo in 1970's Watermelon Man -- without the laughs.
A tightly constructed drama.
White Man's Burden was worth doing once, if it only to find out it isn't worth doing again.
The flaws in this film are many. The dialogue verges on silly when parodying cliches that white people use to denigrate blacks. And most of the acting is just inadequate.
Even if they only charged a token, it would be too much.
The two stars do manage to get off a couple of amusing riffs and Snipes gets to show off some of his kung fu fighting skills, but that's hardly enough to rescue what amounts to a real mess.
It's stupid, but also breezier than the year's other 12-score releases not worth a second look.
Pity poor Wesley Snipes and Woody Harrelson: two gifted actors who must have rotten self-esteem. Why else would they choose to be in a turkey like "Money Train"?
Minor when compared with the masterful Foolish Wives, this 1919 silent feature is nevertheless essential viewing, signaling the arrival of an authentic genius in American cinema.
Careful, the hilariously bizarre new film from Canadian director Guy Maddin, is like some lost masterpiece from a time-warped alternative dimension -- a strange artifact that time forgot.
There's something wonderfully unique about the project but the reasons for doing it remain buried.
Too strange for its own good, Careful is less interesting as a film than it is as a Canadian cinematic anomaly.
It lacks any sense of humor, and is under the delusion that its subjects are interesting because they are great poets. That only makes their poetry interesting.
The Rimbaud seen here is less a poet warrior than cloying brat.
A must for fans and anyone wondering about these supposed corrupters of youth.
An extremely savvy observation on politics in the media age.
Neither bad nor unwatchable, The American President is nevertheless the second straight disappointment from director Rob Reiner.
Great entertainment.
When it comes right down to it, high office does not guarantee high comedy.
Painless fun.
The American President becomes a pretty darn entertaining and affecting movie after its first simpering 20 minutes.
You can't dislike this movie, but you won't be swept away by it either.
The American President will make you laugh and make you smile. But it probably won't make you change your vote.
Essentially a by-the-numbers Hollywood romance in the dopiest melodramatic tradition.
A well-modulated charmer.
Frothy.
Got the same zip as When Harry Met Sally.
Michael Douglas is plausible as president, and he delivers yet another solid, if unmemorable performance.
Charming but flawed leftist romantic comedy.
Douglas and Bening are both wonderful.
Apart from its too-obvious political bias, The American President has romance in its heart, smarts in abundance and class to spare.
A shrewd new depiction of 'office sex,' as well as an utterly positive view of the idea that a president's character is important.
Peppered with terrific performances from a bevy of familiar faces.
A super cast injects it with Teddy Roosevelt vitality.
Rob Reiner seems to have found his calling.
Director Rob Reiner strikes a good balance between drama and old-fashioned love with Douglas and Bening suitably understated in their roles.
'Capraesque' has inevitably been affixed to The American President, but that phrase, with its implications of facile hokum, doesn't do the film justice.
Simplistic, full of stock characters and easy solutions to difficult problems, and I absolutely loved it.
As bustling and impassioned as the best Sturges and Capra movies.

Gold Diggers is not my cup of tea, but it is sure to be enjoyed by younger audiences, and although I don't think it will hold the attention of adults, I do not require adults and children to be alike in all things.
A likable attempt at a teen-girl variation on a Huck Finn-style adventure.
Dig if you must, but this is fool's gold.
These trials suggest a goofy, sprawling, all-purpose allegory so overstuffed with symbolism that it plays as a kind of epic spoof of the form.
Though the film lacks the elegance of Kieslowski's later and better known work, its irony and playfulness presage things to come. Definitely worth checking out if you're a fan.

Father of the Bride Part II is not a great movie and not even as good as its 1991 inspiration (not to mention the Spencer Tracy-Elizabeth Taylor original from 1950). But it is warm and fuzzy, and has some good laughs and a lot of sweetness.
Martin, Keaton and cinematographer William A. Fraker put this retro fluff over better than expected early on, but hour 2 is only for those who don't want their equilibriums rattled by surprises.
In every way -- from the fantastic sets, rich dialogue, and unapologetic violence to the well-portrayed characters and themes of loyalty and betrayal -- Casino is pure Scorsese.
Martin Scorsese's fascinating new film Casino knows a lot about the Mafia's relationship with Las Vegas.
After coming out gangbusters in its first and finest hour, the 180-minute movie loses all its chips in the remaining two.
Scorsese and company do what they do very well -- they've got it down. It's a system unto itself.
Finely detailed analysis of the mob-controlled casinos in the 70s, but it lacks the soul of Scorsese's Goodfellas.
It overstays its welcome.
This bloated three-hour misfire this is a major fumble.
Whether you find it exhilarating, expendable or exhausting -- and you will find it exhausting -- Martin Scorsese's Casino is the spectacular last word on urban sprawl.
Clocking in at three long hours, Casino is an entertaining and engrossing film, but just drags a simple story into a sprawling, epic tale that desperately needs a little trimming.
Scorsese and co. will never make a bad film, only another one.
The movie is good-hearted, earnest and handsome to look at. But it is boring. The pacing, which is meant to be thoughtful, is lethargic.
Apparently, the producers of Jumanji wanted this film to be a Jurassic Park for 1995's holiday season. If so, it's a badly misplaced, and ultimately futile, hope.
A gloomy special-effects extravaganza filled with grotesque images, generating fear and despair.
There's every reason to close up this board game before you've even started.

It's a nifty idea, I guess, even though it is gleefully cynical, but Jumanji and whatever potential it had are undermined by Johnston's inept direction and some cheesy video, digital and computer effects.
Everyone is good here, with Williams taking on the unusual persona of straightman much of the way.
Williams does his usual decent job, and even gets to balance his huggy-bear side with nice sarcastic zingers. But Hunt is the real gem here, her psychobabbling Sarah both funny and appealing.
While it's quite possible for the cinematically unaware to enjoy this film, this is a real treat for movie buffs. The story is as much about the love of motion pictures as it is about gangsters.

One of the pleasures of Get Shorty is watching the way the plot moves effortlessly from crime to the movies - not a long distance, since both industries are based on fear, greed, creativity and intimidation.
By turns satirically glamorous and seedily dark.
Irresistibly charming.

This comic potboiler about gangsters in Hollywood would be a great piece of fun even without Travolta. But as a loan shark from Miami with a charming bedside manner and bigtime movie dreams, he raises the fun quotient into the sublime.
For all its winking and nudging and brightly colored sense of delirium, the movie is also strangely flat.
Very enjoyable, though uneven, comedy comparing the world of organized crime to the world of Hollywood high rollers.
I did enjoy the intermittent good parts and Travolta's performance is a delight, but the rest of the movie is a waste.
One thing is certain: Danny DeVito's production company Jersey Films is turning into a major industry force.
Way too much to absorb in 2 hours, and it results in a talky, sanitized, often boring, tragicomedy that begins to fade from memory as soon as you leave the theater.
This movie is charming the way so few movies are anymore. It's brimming with personality.
It's Hollywood happily mocking itself, with stock characters breaking their molds and digs at everything that is the movie business.
The movie tries for poetry and elegy in its closing scenes, and we can see where it's headed, although it doesn't get there.
The movie itself is a lot of deadwood in the competitive holiday season.

While this curious clash between a near-modern setting and the much older source material might seem confounding, it actually serves to energize the play, as well as making it more palatable to present-day audiences.
The actors are uniformly good, including Broadbent's unctuous Buckingham and Hawthorne's sweet, unsuspecting Clarence.
Setting Richard III in a fictional fascist England of the 1930s is inspired...
A film of rare visual and intellectual vigour, one that challenges while it involves.
Overall, this version of Richard III is an entrancing interpretation.
The best part of the entire movie are the sets by Tony Burrough.
The film's look, opulent with Deco, is stunning, but is never an end in itself.
Flourish is the name of the game, and even what seems like unintentional comedy may be more purposeful than it appears.
The updating is the kind of fanciful exercise far better suited to the stage than to the literal confines of the screen.
McKellen's enormous performance as Richard represents the film's biggest tinkering with theatrical canon.
Combines a shrewd understanding of Shakespeare with a healthy, low-brow approach to cinema.
Few English actors can speak verse with the rhythmic ease and assurance of McKellen and Maggie Smith.
It is ideal for crossover fodder for mainstream audiences.
This is, of course, a big-screen sitcom, and in fact I would love to see this material transplanted to the TV screen, where it belongs.
A wheezier replay of the 1993 hit geezer romp Grumpy Old Men.
... a colossal disappointment.
All the squealing tires, flying bullets and falling bodies cannot save Heat from drowning in its own banalities.
Michael Mann's writing and direction elevate this material. It's not just an action picture.
Heat packs more into one cop movie than the entire genre output of the last five years.
Heat generates lots of energy but gives off little light.
The cop/ crime stuff that makes up the bulk of the movie is well thought out and well directed.

In this riveting, suspenseful action/ drama, two of today's best actors, Oscar winners Al Pacino and Robert De Niro, face off in a plot that's fast-paced and exciting despite a nearly three-hour length.
If there's one thing Michael Mann knows how to do, it's create tension.
As with his other works, [Mann] binds sound, music and pictures into one hypnotic triaxial cable and plugs it right into your brain. He makes this almost-three-hour experience practically glide by.
The cast and the performances in Heat are awesome.
This is a movie about chemistry, straight up.
Director Michael Mann has created a masterpiece.
You can't tell what's important and what isn't, and some may mistake the movie's incoherence for profundity.
Heat runs (sometime crawls) 2:51, but there is really only enough material for two hours.

Boosters and touts use the term 'major movie' so often that it's more likely to generate yawns than excitement at this point. Back to basics. Heat is a major movie. With major stars. Doing major acting.
Heat has an impressively strong script by Mann, and he backs it up with gorgeous filmmaking.
[F]ans of the two stars will probably find it worth their while.
For a film that deserves Oscars for photography, editing, sound and arguably scoring, Heat is packed with unforgettable subcharacters.
... while the sometimes hard-to-follow script often demands too much of the viewer, this film is one that's truly worth seeing.
As notable as the cinematography is De Niro's performance, which helps you remember why he became a legend in the first place.
This is the first time De Niro and Pacino have acted together, and each gives a strong, watertight performance.
There isn't much to recommend this movie until Pacino and De Niro finally share the first of their two scenes together.
All this adds good weight and tension to the movie and provides a lot of very good actors with the opportunity to do honest, probing work in a context where, typically, less will do.
Lively, unpretentious fun.
If you have a taste for Hong Kong action (and I do) then The Legend of Drunken Master has enough going on to make it a classic.
Chan fans will probably want to pay to see this one on the big screen. Everyone else can bide their time for the video release.
The final 20-minute fight sequence ... sets some kind of benchmark: It may not be possible to film a better fight scene.
Watching movies like this, you also understand exactly why the increasingly road-worn Chan simply can't do this kind of stuff anymore. But damn, you'll walk out glad he once could.
While the plot does get in the way of what viewers are really after, there's enough of the fun stuff to keep them interested.
This imported and dubbed Jackie Chan fossil might be a kick for diehard fans, but most will be left feeling high and dry.
Though his antics are comic as ever, what makes this film stand out are the thrilling and frankly beautiful fight sequences.
Beyond all of the fighting and stunts, there isn't much else present to recommend the film.
Everybody should see this film, even if you hate martial arts pictures.
Chan is an entertainer who can singlehandedly make any film enjoyable to watch.
Continuity takes a drubbing and Jackie Chan does his own dubbing in this rerelease of Drunken Master II, a limp Chinese noodle-headed sequel to his 1978 breakthrough feature.
If action fans can take a chance and wade through the unfamiliar settings and awkward dubbing, they'll find an action film that transcends the best of the genre.
[Chan's] as close as film gets to guaranteed entertainment, and he's on top of his game in The Legend of Drunken Master.
A mammothly entertaining picture that represents the best that the traditional kung fu genre has to offer.
Enjoy this rare chance to catch Chan on the big screen at his near-peak mastery.
Great fun for action fans. And if you haven't tried one of these Hong Kong stunt-packed thrillers, this one may get you hooked.
Some of the most impressive Kung Fu fightin' caught on film.
The Legend of Drunken Master contains some of the most impressive action routines ever captured on film.
A bit of a chore to watch for the first half or so. Dubbed dialogue that is totally out of synch doesn't help.
Contains non-stop action of constantly increasing intensity.
Features what are arguably the fastest, most furious and elaborate -- and the most entertaining -- fight sequences ever filmed.
Simply put, there have never been better martial arts put on film.

Not unlike the silent films of Chaplin, Keaton, and Lloyd, or for that matter, the best pictures of Hong Kong's Seventies kung fu films, the genius of Drunken Master lies in its kinetics. Pure entertainment, and a true chop-socky classic.
This is the film where Chan's confidence in his unique mix of comedy and martial arts, his gracefully choreographed slapstick-kung fu fighting style and natural athleticism, really began to blossom.
Unfortunately, it's so dark -- and impenetrable -- that it shuts us out.
Macabre and provocative, yet wonderfully restrained.
Vampires are compared to junkies who need their fix.
Not to everyone's taste but certainly haunting in theme and visuals.
The Addiction is less a blood-sucking story than a fable about modern enervation.
Eternally heavy-handed director Abel Ferrara isn't interested in making anything that even remotely resembles a conventional horror film.
Ferrara sinks his teeth into a moral fable that equates bloodlust with amorality and postulates that there may, even now, be salvation for the sinner.
The film works better as straight horror -- it's quite gory and the inky black-and-white photography adds intensely to the mood -- than as a meditation on morality.
Despite the unambitious, formula-driven plot, wonderful performances by Julia Ormond and, especially, Harrison Ford keep this remake afloat.
Hampered by an unimaginative script ... nevertheless manages to be a thoroughly charming, delightfully romantic variation of the Cinderella story.
Just as satisfying, if not as dry and cynical, as the original.
A light fairy-tale, sweet and charming.
Has a level of complexity rare in contemporary Hollywood.
Never evokes the sweet allure of Billy Wilder's original film.
The remake, alas, must mask its failings with Julia Ormond's toothsomeness, Pollack's poky pacing and the uninspired scribblings of writers Barbara Benedek and David Rayfiel.
It's likable, and nostalgic.
Harrison Ford and Julia Ormond have great chemistry.
A surprisingly delightful and fresh romance.
Polished, classy
While it can't hold a candle to Wilder's film, the updated Sabrina has its moments.
A handsome remake that plays homage to the Wilder flick.
Ford's deadpan delivery is perfect, and television talk-show host Kinnear is very funny in his first big-screen performance.
Sydney Pollack miraculously almost pulls off his updated homage simply by choosing well and popping enough champagne corks to make us believe the wealthy are still glamorous despite Donald Trump.
A warm and clever romantic comedy that stands on its own and offers a good time for two hours -- despite its myriad implausibilities.
Stands on its own, without odious comparison, as an entertaining love story, particularly if you've never seen the original.
Rich with the kind of conversation that most movies, even romances, don't even aspire to.

Sunrise (1927) is German director F. W. Murnau's compelling American debut - his first project for Hollywood's Fox Film Corporation (and William Fox), but planned in Germany. It was the first feature film released with synchronized sound-on-film
Sunrise is an incredible achievement, and perhaps the greatest silent drama ever made.
Asked if I wanted to see it again, I figured, why not? I would have remembered if it was really bad. But memory does play tricks.
Regardless of its dated stylishness (which still holds up remarkably well a decade plus later), Heavy Metal was a pioneering film in 1981 and remains a pivitol and infuential body of art today.
This animated movie based on the comics of the same title is fun once you accept it on its own terms, i.e., brainless and adolescent.
A genuinely outrageous and occasionally brilliant coupling of American animation and classic early-Eighties heavy metal.
This is simply exploitation on a very juvenile level.
A wildly sophomoric and stupid cartoon celebrating gore, rape and bad music.
The action and stunts are spectacular and entertaining, but big time Jet Li fans will be ultimately disappointed with the dull and predictable story.
There isn't much of a story. The minimal plot exists exclusively to get the orangutan Dunston (played by "Sam") into as many odd, potentially-comic circumstances as possible.
Dunston Checks In -- Wish I hadn't.
Bed of Roses tells a sappy story about two sad sacks who get more or less what they deserve -- each other.
Don't blame the leads, but the movie has less emotional resonance than an old FTD florist commercial with Merlin Olsen.
It's a bucolic epic about the Soviet struggle to collectivize agricultural production, and it's far from his least interesting or exciting film.
Penn gives an astonishing performance and delivers exactly what Dead Man Walking needs.
Dead Man Walking could easily be manipulative or exploitative, but it's neither. Instead, this is hard-hitting drama that neither accepts nor offers quarter.
The picture is cloudy in intent.
Absorbing, surprising, technically superb and worth talking about for a long time afterward
This makes you think harder about crime and punishment than, say, The Green Mile, delivering uneasy truths rather than comforting melodrama.
A daring stand and a daring, uncompromised film.
Don't go unadvised, and don't plan anything too frivolous for right afterwards. But do go.
Sarandon, who won the Oscar for Best Actress for this role, is superb, but Penn is extraordinary.
Robbins, who also wrote the script, is no Truman Capote, let alone a Victor Hugo, and his film trips up constantly on indecisiveness about what it is he's trying to say.
A thought-provoking drama not to be missed or dismissed.
Robbins and Susan Sarandon, have crafted a film that transcends its own political message by a scrupulous attention to detail.
An entirely superb experience at the movies, but never have we seen anything on the big screen reduce grown men to tears like this drama.
A painfully honest portrayal of the dark side and the dignity a decent person can bring to the most horrific of situations.
It will make you think about its specific subject matter -- capital punishment -- in emotional, moral, social and political contexts, all intertwined and none reducible to right or wrong.
Expresses a heartfelt opinion on the death penalty without seeming either preachy or one-sided.
A tour de force acting performance by Sarandon.
It will send you home with more than a few long thoughts.

One of the best things a film can do is make us reflect on our convictions and beliefs. Dead Man Walking powerfully forces this reflection through its compellingly ambiguous subject matter and superb performances by Sarandon and Penn.
Its objectivity is what makes it so controversial and fascinating.
A profoundly affecting film that will touch you deeply and perhaps even prompt you to re-examine your notions about the issues at hand.
is the finest, least compromised film about capital punishment ever advancing a gently stated 'anti' view but going the extra 100 miles to give victims their due.
It probably isn't for everyone, but Dead Man Walking is a tale that needs to be heard and that will likely provide material for hours of philosophical debate.
Acting rarely gets better than this.
This feels like a giant cop-out.
Its final moments leave us awash in emotion.
It obviously has its moments, but most of the way this is pretty tepid stuff. We've seen it all before.
If King of the Hill couldn't draw patrons despite appearing on tons of 10-best lists, what's a comparably themed small-change remembrance gonna do?
We go expecting to be inspired and uplifted, and we leave somewhat satisfied in those areas, but with reluctant questions about how well the story has aged, and how relevant it is today.
Especially heart-rending thanks to superb performances by James Earl Jones and Richard Harris.
Four Rooms has to be one of 1995's major disappointments.
The four segments are widely different in quality. On the useful scale of the Michelin guides, one is worth a trip, another is worth a detour, and the other two are a colossal waste of bandwidth.
Four Rooms asserts itself as a goof so laboriously and aggressively that you almost feel pinned back in your seat.
The segments are uniformly weak.
This is a gimmick movie.
Anthology films never work; Tarantino is not infallible; casting Madonna as a lesbian witch and Bruce Willis in a silly party hat doesn't necessarily make for great entertainment.
A stunt anthology blunders horrifically.
Results in a wildly uneven, temperamental, and ultimately disappointing mish-mash of cameos, in-jokes, and stories that fail to engage.
If anything, it may give pause to those who think Tarantino can do no wrong.
Four Rooms has been cut substantially since a disastrous September reception at the Toronto Film Festival, though it's hard to imagine it running any longer.
An over-anticipated, overworked movie that was full of talent but devoid of taste.
The result is a batch of shrill, self-indulgent sketches that turn so wretched in spots you start to wonder if the filmmakers wanted them to be bad.
Maybe if you're a young, raw Hollywood aspirant, you believe that it's a sign of sophistication to be unrattled by the bizarre.
Georgia is not a simply plotted movie about descent and recovery, but a complex, deeply knowledgeable story about how alcoholism and mental illness really are family diseases.
Leigh's performance is riveting.
A painful though sadly humorous portrait of sisterhood deftly written by Leigh's mom, Barbara Turner, and directed with just-right spareness by Ula Grosbard.
Unless you're just dying to hear Velvet Underground tunes played (badly) at bar mitzvahs, I'd recommend keeping this Georgia off your mind.
A brilliantly complex character study with a dynamic lead performance by Anthony Hopkins.
Factual or not, there's no denying that Nixon has moments when it is nothing short of compelling.
The picture is a case study.

Thoughts of Hamlet, Macbeth and King Lear come to mind; here, again, is a ruler destroyed by his fatal flaws. There's something almost majestic about the process: As Nixon goes down in this film, there is no gloating, but a watery sigh, as of a great ship
There's no compelling structure or viewpoint to hold the picture together.
Casting Anthony Hopkins was a stroke of unexpected genius.
Stone's no Shakespeare, and neither are his screenwriters.
I never felt that I was seeing the darkness reaching out to the darkness as Nixon was once described.
Anthony Hopkins's audaciously theatrical, profoundly moving portrait of Richard Nixon richly deserves the adjective 'Shakespearean.'
You will not be bored.
A monumental achievement in cinema about a small, pathetic figure in U.S. history.
It's grand-scale moviemaking, but eventually its scope and polish are less compelling than its messiness and incompleteness.
The president's tale is convoluted as it is, and doesn't need the assistance of Stone's dizzying mix of film stocks, camera angles and jump cuts, or his non-Euclidean plot flow.
Thoughtful, well-researched and carefully modulated, the film also marks director Oliver Stone's coming of age.
Rich, dense and complex.
You never feel Hopkins' performance was anything less than an Oscar-worthy re-creation.
Joan Allen goes beyond her chilling physical resemblance to Pat Nixon toward serious Oscar worthiness.
The problem here isn't accuracy. It's absurdity.
Lapses in tone give the film a schizophrenic quality.
Real life, if it's real Nixon, is more dramatic than an Oliver Stone movie.
An overwrought Disney weeper.
If you are a jazz aficionado, an Australian film connoisseur, or both, Dingo might be the film for you.
Take the kids. Have fun.
Oliver & Company is a funny, zestful, colorful cartoon, created with quality animation that blends well-rounded cel painting and smooth computer-generated drawings.
Why these juvenile delinquents and their even worse masters are considered appropriate material for the 3-8 set that is most likely to see this movie is a conundrum.
This is a funny, enjoyable family treat.
Despite three screenwriters and 13 names credited for the story, the script quickly sinks into a predictable 'girl-meets-pet, girl-loses-pet, girl-and -pet-reunite' sap-trap.
Seen today, Oliver & Company comes across as a rather shabby transitional work, one that lacks the sophistication of today's 'toons and doesn't hold up to the Disney classics of yesteryear.
It does a better job than most family films in projecting a child's-eye view of a world where siblings and pets are equally cherished members of the family.
The first movie was good-hearted and I liked it, but since then Babe has raised the bar, with animals that not only talk more realistically, but say things that are wittier and more pungent.
Wee urbanites might find Disney's scorn for city life a shade offputting, but if preview audiences are any indication, little ones will laugh their tiny heinies off at the humor herein.
Full of the cute doggie tricks, big noisy adventure sequences and the usual anthropomorphic bits of action and dialogue that children will love.
The plot is nothing more than a recycled version of the first one, but hey, it is still funny and there are many great lines.
A silly little trifle with more wisecracks than laughs.
It's more padded than Lassie's bed. But 9-and-unders were having a tail-wagging good time.
Taken on its own entirely hokey terms, Homeward Bound II: Lost in San Francisco is a charming romp of a talking animal movie.
Like the first Homeward Bound, this one has some very nice elements, including wonderful camera work.
Thompson is outstanding, but her supporting cast is just as impressive, if not more so.
Told with deft skill and a pleasantly humorous romantic touch.
Sense and Sensibility is an enjoyable film, and yet it left me somehow unsatisfied.
A triumph for Taiwan's most famous director, Ang Lee.
Thompson's script hits its peak by keeping Austen's voice yet finding the satirical smirk behind it.
Sense and Sensibility is funny, expansive, and a delight to spend company with.
The best film of the year.
Demonstrates how little humankind has evolved in matters of the heart.
A movie for all romantic ages that won't even dispirit singles.
Rickman's small moves, his lowered eyes, his slight grimaces, are often quite breathtaking.
Wonderful adaptation of Jane Austen's novel.
A soap opera of the highest caliber.
It's bliss.
Sense and Sensibility is an absorbing, delightful, and nuanced movie.
Exquisitely detailed and impeccably acted.
A glorious return to old-fashioned filmmaking at its best.
A heartfelt story, filled with rich characters and compelling events.
The movie is good fun, boasting a dozen vivid characters and two that moviegoers will take to heart.
A memorable film that brings out everything we love about these kinds of stories.
Thompson is amazing in her mostly quiet way.
The film is packed with pleasing performances by stage-trained actors.
An exuberant, well- crafted film that gets the audience involved on a gut level.
What a glorious time is had by all in this wonderful adaptation of Jane Austen's novel.
Despite paying lip service to high ideals, Schlesinger's movie has no moral compass, and is only interested in delivering cheap thrills.
This movie is intellectually corrupt because it deliberately avoids dealing with the issues it raises.
A nasty, incompetent piece of work.
Director John Schlessinger presents a film about grief, justice and revenge that feels lifted from the TV-movie of the week.
A poorly acted, manipulative, and ridiculous soap opera.
By showing this in graphic, R-rated terms (albeit with quick, MTV-style edits), the scene's power is diluted and the film's exploitative tendencies are revealed early on.
A grimly distasteful revenge thriller masquerading as serious social commentary.
While the tension slowly builds up over the course of the film, it never quite makes it to where it desperately needed to go.
The film, like a TV show that paints everything in black and white and aims for tabloid-style shock value, proceeds along predictable lines.
With a target as nasty as he, when Karen wants to take the law into her own hands, you can't help thinking, Go to it.
Not a single moment of this film is a surprise.
No masterpiece, but a prime example of subversive cinema.
An Unforgettable Summer is spare and direct in telling its story, and is well cast.

Angels and Insects is like the dark underside of a Merchant-Ivory film; in one scene, we visit a sunny, pastoral clearing in the woods, and lift up a rock to see the plump, slimy little slugs and larvae beneath, dining on each other.
No matter what you think this adaptation of A.S. Byatt's novella Morpho Eugenia sounds like, it's better and certainly kinkier than your best parlor-game guess.

Without revealing plot twists, I will say that the movie goes on a long while -- a very long while -- after the trial is over, and that a trip to the jungles of Guatemala is unnecessary, to put it mildly.
Moore needs The Juror like she needs another scarlet letter; the 'D-for-dopey' here is hanging down to everyone's knees.
Though it takes a while to get moving, Twelve Monkeys becomes a thrilling, haunting and exceedingly well-acted film.
A consistently engaging motion picture.
What's remarkable about 12 Monkeys is that, despite its decade-hopping abandon, the film makes a chilling kind of narrative sense.
As an entertainment, it appeals more to the mind than to the senses.
In some ways, 12 Monkeys is the end-of-the-world thriller that Kathryn Bigelow's Strange Days wanted to be.

At one point Cole says that viewing the past is like watching a good movie, 'Every time you see it it's different, because you're different.' 12 Monkeys is a film that will do that, change as you change.
This film hits a nerve a lot more effectively than either the director's Brazil or The Fisher King.
Willis gives a quietly intense performance, looking like he's trying to solve a jigsaw puzzle in his head.
An intoxicating blend of existential SF and unrequited romance.
A densely plotted, visually dynamic post-apocalyptic thriller.
The sort of movie that disappears on you as soon as you leave the theatre, but it's a great ride while you're there.
The film is intelligently written, and deserves more than its guaranteed cult-film status.
A movie that is about as much fun to watch as getting your teeth pulled.

It has a story -- and a good one at that -- with characters one cares about and isn't just a flashy display of what today's special effects teams are capable of. Anybody out there in Hollywood listening to any of this?
Overwrought.
This is action movie-making at its most suave.
Aside from his trademark visual style, Gilliam generally handles the chaos he depicts quite well, and he's come up with a marvelous cast.
Despite my beef with the interminable convolutions of 12 Monkeys, the film has one major thing going for it: put simply, it's very, very cool.
I'm pleased beyond words to find a movie that cares deeply for its characters even as they fall under the wheels of destiny, instead of killing them just to be clever.
A potent glimpse of doom with a jarringly familiar ring.
One of the qualities that makes 12 Monkeys so good is the fact that it is almost too complicated to explain.
In its frantic mix of chaos, carnage and zoo animals, 12 Monkeys is Jumanji for adults.
Shanghai Triad plays like a movie in which some scenes are missing, and others have been stretched out to make up the difference.
Shanghai Triad concludes the sublime seven-movie collaboration of Chinese filmmaker Zhang Yimou and actress Gong Li with a bang worthy of the most jubilant New Year's Eve.
A giddy triple somersault of a film that makes no sense whatsoever, although in its best moments it is as much fun to watch as a death-defying circus act.
A true original at work, a man who can take a ski, a pinball machine or a football helmet and make them part of his own graceful brand of art.

Unlike most action stars, Chan understands acting. His face is as flexible as his body, and, when he's moving, he's like a violent, supercharged combination of Gene Kelly, Fred Astaire, and Buster Keaton.
The whole point is Jackie Chan - and, like Astaire and Rogers, he does what he does better than anybody.
As the star cheerfully camouflages massive bandages on a twisted ankle, we also get a glimpse of just how far Chan is willing to go to please his audience.
Chan, doing everything at once including all his own stunts, has an infectious energy that will help to remind you why you love movies.
The fun of Rumble in the Bronx is watching Chan build up one inventive and off-the-wall action scene after another.

The very medium of the moving picture exists to create the suspension of disbelief, and there is no greater live performer than Chan to make us believe you can beat up a street gang with a linen jacket and refrigerators.
Awe-inspiring.
Chan is his usual amazing self onscreen.
It's not often you find a movie as exciting and awful as Rumble in the Bronx.
Rumble is nonstop action.

It's set in New York but made in the more affordable Vancouver, the plot makes no sense, the costumes are from some '80s timewarp, the acting ranges from lousy to a little better, the dialogue dubbing is atrocious. And the movie is pretty terrific.
If you are an action fan, and haven't seen Chan before, definitely see this film. If you don't have the taste for the genre, however, there is absolutely nothing here to draw you in.
Even though you know what's coming up, it's damn compelling stuff.
The story is nothing more than a thin veneer and a poor one at that over a movie to show off the martial arts talents of Jackie Chan.
More than a martial arts whiz, the 41-year-old Chan possesses the comic timing of a born clown, the grace of a Broadway hoofer and the daredevil bravado of an Evel Knievel.
Despite the picture's numerous shortcomings, Rumble in the Bronx still packs more laughs and inventive action than most of Hollywood's jaded action product.
The film may look amateurish, but the camera-work is fluid, the best to catch Chan's choreography.
You can smirk at Rumble and deny its pedigree with some justification, as long as you concede that it's 10 times more fun to watch than Before and After and Mary Reilly put together.

Jackie Chan kicks butt, gets beat up, kicks more butt, survives a collapsing building, skis in his sneakers behind a hovercraft, foils a heist, befriends a motorcycle gang, falls in love, and attends his uncle's wedding. What more could you want?
An awkward hybrid of Asian and American film techniques.
The most fun-loving film of the current season.
Giddy, surprising and raucous fun.
As the guy who cleans up a ghetto, helps a crippled kid and does battle with a rampaging Hovercraft, Chan shows off the muscle of a superhero and the charm of a deft comedian.
I enjoyed its visuals, its evocative soundtrack (including a suite for percussion and heavy breathing), and its ideas.
Ghost in the Shell is another 'Japanamation' feature, with a science-fiction story that is a bit more interesting than most, though it is also overly complicated and occasionally confusing.
Mamoru Oshii's direction deftly merges gritty realism with a dreamlike quality.
If you try focusing on the plot particulars, Ghost is frustrating and, despite the gunfire, not entirely dramatic. But as a piece of dark art, it's substantial and successful.

This is a promising premise, but somehow Broken Arrow never really sinks in its teeth and takes it seriously. Consider, for example, the scene where we discover Travolta is not what he seems. He turns to Slater in the cockpit and... narrows his eyes.
Directed with the keen action instincts Woo brought to The Killer, Hard-Boiled and other cult causes from his career in Hong Kong.
Happy's tantrums, which the movie pretends are liberating explosions of self-expression, aren't nearly maniacal enough to reach comic delirium.
Sandler's movie is worth a few laughs, but not many of the comic sequences are original, and even fewer are inspired.
The Happy Gilmore character is strange. I guess we are supposed to like him.
Happy Gilmore may not be an ace in the hole, but it beats par by a long shot.
Happy Gilmore does often make the viewer burst out laughing.

A lame, unoriginal comedy that may offer a few scattered chuckles, but more often than not, serves up a bewildering series of bizarre non-jokes, supposedly ironic product placement, cheesy music cues, and tired sight gags.
To my own surprise, I laughed a lot.
The story has all the thickness of a well-trimmed green, but it's a decent excuse for some heady sight gags.
The Bob Barker/Happy Gilmore fistfight and Ben Stiller's uncredited cameo as an evil nursing home manager make this one worth a lazy Sunday rental.

Sandler plays this a lot smarter than, say, a Jim Carrey character, and with less slapstick. Still, this is not delicate, subtle stuff: It's smart low-brow, and only for those who like their humor a bit offbeat.
As dumb as Caddyshack was, though, it seems like George Bernard Shaw compared to this poor stepchild. Back to stand-up, Adam Sandler.
...a movie that happens before it thinks.
As directed sloppily by Nick Castle, this comedy barely lets its main characters develop, even though either of them could be great fun.
This is a romantic comedy parody, but how can you satirize something that's a comedy to begin with? If this motion picture is an example, not only can't it be done, but the result is downright ugly.
A sour, listless debunking of romantic comedies.
A clumsy, repetitive attempt at comedy.
Any movie that has the word "wrong" in the title should be very, very careful to get things right. The makers of this movie were not careful.
There are places where even Matheson and Castle seem ill-at-ease with their own premise, as if they are trying to make both a dark satire and a bright, light comedy. The result is like oil and water.
Like its title character, Mr. Wrong doesn't know when to quit.
This film offers just about everything, including a twenty-minute white-knuckle sequence and a chance to shed a few tears. In short, it's first-rate entertainment.
I enjoyed the movie for the sheer physical exuberance of its adventure.
The movie's a shipload of coming-of-age blather, supplemented with enough rolling-sea footage to make the audience yearn for both Dramamine and a decent drowning scene.
The heavy-handedness of these final scenes will probably ruin the movie for some people, while others will enjoy its earnestness and energy. Count me among the latter group.

The visuals throughout the movie are exhilarating, and the squall scene in particular is pulled off spectacularly (if a bit chaotically). The scene is so powerful, it almost washes away the taint of familiarity...almost.
This picture has nothing original to say, and the acting is way below par. Imagine making a show about kids and then not putting in a single kid (or adult for that matter) that you care about.
The script is slow and tired. We've seen it all before, and the change of setting has little impact.
Far too much of this handsomely mounted adventure is devoted to routinely dramatized adolescent minutiae.
While the denouement is basically another bummer of a letdown, you'll still be coming off that adrenaline rush from the 'squall' scenes.
Director Ridley Scott, who more than anyone else founded post-1960s visceral filmmaking, is at the top of his form in White Squall.
Although only slightly more than two hours, the film seems becalmed for days in what seems a dramatic doldrum.

The storm sequence is worth the wait, as scary and dramatically filmed as any ocean disaster you've seen in the movies, but the tribunal that follows is so muddled as to end the film in a great big anti-climax.
It's so overwritten it becomes an exercise in style rather than a story about its characters. On balance, I think it's an interesting miss.
Yet another debut about urban lowlifes filmed by wanna-be Tarantinos, Denver boasts a distinctive personality and a colorful cast that any police lineup would be proud to call its own.
Solid entertainment, especially in a season when Hollywood's releases are repeatedly causing grimaces.
Restoration avoids the pitfalls of pious historical reconstructions and plunges right into the cauldron.
A garishly gilded, gloriously overstuffed costume drama.
Even in period drag, this movie resembles warmed-over Forrest Gump.
An incredible exercise in style.

Even when all decked out in foppish finery, looking absolutely ridiculous to the objective eye, [Downey] can't find a way to focus your attention on him. Instead, in looking at him, all you can do is wonder: How much did those duds cost?
Two movies for the price of one.
What virtues the movie has are cosmetic.
One of the most exquisitely rendered period pieces I've ever seen, replete with fully-laden palaces and disgustingly realistic plague victims.

While this sly and sumptuous new film offers just the single word as its title, it will make you think of all you learned about Restoration comedy -- and drama -- in that long-ago History of the Theater 101 course.

Hoffman proves himself a master of complex scenery, crowd control and graceful direction. He succeeds in making a conspicuously lush and rich movie out of what was reportedly a less than kingly budget.
Somewhere in this potentially fascinating story of a man's life, the director caught epic fever and his characters got buried in breadth and depth of his ambition.
It's great fun, but certainly not great art.
The movie, which treats you with contempt for even watching it, is a monument to its own lack of imagination.
What we have here in From Dusk Till Dawn is Pulp Fiction with teeth.

It's clever, brash and -- if you're into it -- entertaining movie-making that has it all ways, allowing you a stylishly cynical noninvestment, alongside an old-fashioned attachment to the regular guy.
Fans of the genre will like it, especially in the no-holds barred second half. Others are advised to avoid this one.
This is horror with a wink and a nod to drive-in theatres and sweaty back seats. This is how it's done.
The sickest, most perverted movie within memory. Guiltily, I liked it. But what the hell is it?

The film is so flamboyantly gory and disgusting, so vulgar and in-your-face obnoxious, with so many offensive subplots and wacked-out elements that you may give up long before you need to reach for your second headache tablet.
As the bloodsuckers attack our 'heroes' again and again, you feel like you're watching a video game -- from dusk to dawn.
The way-over-the-top campiness is so completely ridiculous, it's impossible to take anything in the film seriously. And trust me, that's not a bad thing.
I don't mean to dismiss his films, which I enjoy, or cast aspersions on his character, but I've got to admit -- when Tarantino plays his own sordid parts, he gives me the creeps.
The filmmakers' references, their winks and nods to the audience, are far more diverting than the picture itself.

From Dusk Till Dawn was probably spawned from an all night bender during which Tarantino and Rodriguez thought it would be fun to see if they could make a deliberately lame movie with someone else's money.
Tashlin had a huge stylistic impact on the New Wave. Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter?, his greatest film, is the template for Godard's bold use of primary colors and 'Scope in the 60s.
Aging but still funny.
Rohmer's impossibly light, graceful way of posing profound moral questions hasn't yet wholly coalesced, though this 1966 film does have his soft, slow rhythm.
They're certainly no Aykroyd and Belushi, or even Myers and Carvey, but Farley and Spade manage to wring humor from a series of juvenile setups and predictable pratfalls.
[Farley] is funny in the great loser buffoon tradition of guys who look like they slept through shop class but graduated from the two year tech course anyway.
Utter, unforgivable bilge.
It is one long, drawn out exercise in pain.
Black Sheep is an appropriately titled misfire, a des-perate slapstick comedy that falls flat at nearly every turn.

Black Sheep is bleatingly awful as it reteams Chris Farley and David Spade, the poor idiot's Abbott and Costello, in a comedy so desperately inept it makes their previous effort, Tommy Boy, look like a minefield of high wit.
Yeah, I giggled a couple of times. But I suspect you will giggle more if you are male, age 15-27ish.
Spade plays the straight man, Farley plays the dufus, physical stunts abound and there isn't one shred of slightly intellectual wit.
I've never wanted to run from a theater so much in my life.

To its credit, "Jack and Sarah" eschews the standard cutesy-poo shenanigans found in movies where adorable infants run inexperienced adults ragged with their needs. Unfortunately, the movie has very little comedy to offer in place of such antics.

The screenplay, by Tim Sullivan (who also directs), is straight off the assembly line. But by casting against type, by finding an actor whose very presence insists he is not to be disregarded, the movie works in spite of its conventions.
"Jack & Sarah" is one of those romantic movies viewers know will end in a happy smooch. What's fine is the rush of amusing, heartrending humanity before it gets to the inevitable.
The movie's big problem is Mathis, who not only can't act but also is given a rather unattractive role to play.
Hate is, I suppose, a Generation X film, whatever that means, but more mature and insightful than the American Gen X movies.
All the performances are excellent, especially Cassel...

Writer-director Mathieu Kassovitz mines so much tension and pointed dialogue from a low budget and deceptively simple premise that you wonder why so much of current Hollywood's own social realism ends up shooting $50 million blanks.
It's more three-dimensional and realistic, showing how death, for all of its sadness, can sometimes create joy, if people are given the opportunity to affirm what they feel for one another.
This Party has its funny, sad and awkward moments. But at the end, you'll be glad you went.
Ambitious but mainly unsuccessful.
Mr. LeBlanc ... is so blank that the only impression he makes is of having teeth that are very large and unnaturally white.

The movie is breathtakingly unadventurous, with its cheesy story line, hackneyed ballpark-fable sentiments, "adorable" animal and collection of one-dimensional human nincompoops, headed by Matt LeBlanc
One of the worst, most wrong-headed "family" fantasies to come along in some time.
It's forgettable matinee fodder.
There's never a moment when you think it's a real chimp, so even that novelty is nonexistent.
Much of the movie will make no sense to someone looking for more than a parade of potty jokes.
The tone of the acting, which is set by Mr. Grammer's blandly laid-back performance, is all wrong for a genre that demands over-the-top hamming.
There are occasional laughs, but, as with most movies that think they're funnier than they actually are, most of the jokes fall flat.
More laid-back here than he is on television, Grammer seems to barely break a sweat.
Down Periscope is a rather leaky sub.
There's barely a belly laugh here, and judging from the deafening silence in the theatre where I saw the film, it's not just me.
Some of this is silly and dumb as jokes fall flat. But there are also some laughs to be had.
A soggy sub sandwich layered with cheesy action, stale jokes and gung-ho baloney.
Yes, I think I can hear you not laughing, right now.
After that auspicious opening, it sinks.
Why give someone who has a genuine skill for understated, intelligent comedy a highly unfunny script that's both overly obvious and stupid?
This maritime comedy is not worth watching without something else to do.
Screamers oozes atmosphere. It's a dark film that borrows heavily from the likes of the Alien films, Dune, Blade Runner, and John Carpenter's updated The Thing.
It's not exactly a bad movie; it's made with a certain imagination and intelligence. But its future is so grungy and grim it makes our current mess look like Utopia.
The movie ends with a weak gimmick, and leaves you with the feeling that it could have done better had it had more trust in itself and its own concepts.
It remains reasonably faithful to the original short story, the production values are okay and some of the dialogue is pretty effective.

Might just as well have gone straight to video instead of movie-theater screens, since it is every bit as cheesy, underdeveloped and gore-filled as the tape-rentals that fill sci-fi/horror shelves monthly.
A pile of recycled space junk, it alienates even while flinging body parts into the audience's yawning faces.
In its last minutes Screamers becomes the last thing it intends to be -- laughable.
It's one of those movies that is bad enough to be boring and incomprehensible, but not bad enough (most of the time) to be reprehensible or riotously funny.
Screamers is inundated with movie cliches, stock characters, stolen premises and scenes that just don't make sense.
I suppose it all could somehow have been made funny, but not by the people who made this movie.
For sheer impact, this Othello can stand side-by-side with the versions brought to the screen by Orson Welles (as restored in 1992) and Lawrence Olivier.
... Will not give its viewers much of an idea of the Shakespeare play, and may inadvertently give them other ideas, about interracial love, that were not much on Shakespeare's mind.
Parker, whose screenplay strips down the original play, merely produces a lackluster essence.
Passion, like outpourings of iambic pentameter, isn't part of this picture's equation.
Fishburne, Jacob, and Branagh make Parker's version of Othello a chilling and horrific tragedy.
There is little to offend in the movie, but neither is there much to engage the audience.
Purists may grumble about changes, but even in this abridged form, Shakespeare's language and storytelling seem preserved quite well.
The movie is roughly on the same cinematic level as the Mel Gibson Hamlet, though it tends to get under your skin a little more once it gets rolling.
Seldomly have I been so outright disappointed by a film.
The real question is, could director Oliver Parker have done worse?
It almost works. Except when Shakespeare, Parker or the actors get in the way.
The film Lawrence Fishburne will be remembered for.
The City of Lost Children is as visually striking and daringly offbeat as its predecessor.
Many people will probably not find themselves sympathetic to this movie's overachieving technological pretensions, while others will find it the best film in months or years.
If City of Lost Children lacks something in narrative innovation, it's plainly invested in picking through the mucky ugliness that supports these familiar moral configurations.
Astounding imagery combine with bizarre characters and comedy in this dark and twisted French fairy tale.
There is a lot going for City of Lost Children and if you're up to something 'different' for change then it is definitely worth a rental.
With its fine performances, gorgeous sets, incredible special effects, imaginative story line, beautiful score, and knockout cinematography, The City of Lost Children is very much worth seeing.
Another wacky and dark and visually dazzling film by the makers of Delicatessen.
Children hasn't enough of a human dimension to be 'fun' itself, but it's still warped enough to amuse anyone with a tilted frame of mind.

The City of Lost Children pushes style to the limit, while occasionally causing substance to lag behind. While the movie sometimes gets so convoluted it's impossible to tell exactly what's going on, it's always fun to watch.
Would that a movie this wondrous weren't simultaneously so formulaic.

The City of Lost Children is a series of associated visual stimuli so imaginative and omnivorous that their spectacle has the effect of wearing us out. Nevertheless, if you think of yourself as warped, you really must see this.

The French fantasy adventure The City of Lost Children is a dark phantasmagoria so visually amazing and provocative -- yet dense and confusing -- that viewers may need to see it more than once to take it all in.
I'm not really sure who would enjoy this movie. It's a little too rich for most people's digestions.
Highly recommended, but you should go prepared to squirm along with the host, hostess, and guests.
A good, taut movie for red-meat action audiences.
For uncomplicated excitement, the film offers a solid one-hundred thirty minutes.
A movie for people who are sophisticated enough to know how shameless the film is, but fun-loving enough to enjoy its excesses and manic zeal.
Deliciously turbulent.
Executive Decision is just about what you'd expect in the action genre.
The film is well done, well executed and the best action film to come along in a long while.
So, is your adrenaline a little low? Suffer from low blood pressure? Have I got a cure for you: Executive Decision.
It doesn't always work, but there's something inspiring about Baird's unwillingness to follow the usual formula.
There's nothing like a protracted action drama in which anti-terrorist commandos slink around the bowels of an airborne 747 and talk about what they hope to accomplish upstairs in the final shootout.
If you go to Executive Decision, sit back and try to enjoy the explosions and high-tech gadgetry. But more importantly, try to get there late.
Stuart Baird's direction is so sluggish and Jim and John Thomas' script so padded that Executive Decision has no build.
Russell never really gets your blood going.
A moronic buddy comedy with a fuzzy-wuzzy coating.
The entire setup is too garish to be credible.
Aside from a lot of only moderately-satisfying violence, The Substitute comes across as rather lame.
The title changes, the actors change, and the superficial details of the story change, but it is always about exactly the same thing: heavily armed men shooting at one another.
There's a certain amount of camp value to this over-the-top thriller, which might as well be called Rambo Goes to High School.
An angry, white, mercenary movie out to spill blood and beat its manly chest.
Settles for being a deranged version of The A-Team meets The Principal.
Because The Substitute doesn't take itself seriously, it's a great deal of lowbrow fun.
A poorly written and barely acted, but crowd-pleasing revenge flick.
The silliness of The Substitute escalates as the film progresses, so that by the end there have been plenty of laughs during 'serious' scenes.
Those who appreciate the irony of a killing machine turned loose on a pack of nasty students will find The Substitute a source of nonstop delight.
This movie is a lot more entertaining than the Michelle Pfeiffer showcase Dangerous Minds.
It's one of those movies where you want to call out helpful advice to the screen, which would save the characters a lot of trouble.
Despite Meryl Streep, Liam Neeson and the usually estimable Edward Furlong, this nonevent huffs and puffs to attain even the level of an ordinary motion picture.
fares poorly when constrained to the screen
The temptations are great to mock the cliches and melodrama in Up Close & Personal, but the movie undeniably works as what it really is -- a love story.
This is one of those untaxing time-killers where you spend a lot of time pondering which of its actress's changing hairstyles you like best.
Needless to say, the gore level is high and the scare level low -- although not as low as the intelligence level.
Unfortunately, while director Joe Chapelle and writer Daniel Farrands took advantage of a clearance sale at the Horror Cliche Emporium, they forgot to stop in at Plots R Us.
There isn't a floorboard that doesn't creak, a person who doesn't hesitate to go down the basement, a killing that isn't telegraphed by scary music and laughable attempts at tension.
The less said about this sixth entry in the Halloween series, the better.
The film's conclusion is, naturally, open-ended, to allow for Halloween 7, which will probably be subtitled Michael Myers Does a Pepsi Commercial.
This sixth installment, by far the worst in the series, is bland and deadening.
Too Much is a screwball comedy in every ounce of its being. A bad one, true, but screwball all the same.
Interesting if somewhat didactic.
Buuel is still able to put some bizarre -- and very funny -- personal touches on this story of a man obsessed with the idea that the music box he owned as a child has the power to kill.
Muppet Treasure Island, directed by Brian Henson, son of the late Muppet genius, will entertain you more or less in proportion to your affection for the Muppets.

Geena Davis and Renny Harlin couldn't cut it with Cutthroat Island. Steven Spielberg nearly got the hook for Hook. But leave it to Miss Piggy and Kermit to discover uncharted gold in the shipwrecked-pirate genre.
Rarely has a film more movingly shown how people who work, live and pray together can find a common strength and self-respect.
The acting is good all round, but the star of the show has to be Al Freeman Jr. He shows great inner strength, bravery, and intelligence.
Though the film exhibits a vaguely nostalgic tone, it's hardly sugar-coated, displaying an increasingly discernible edge to its portrayal of racist realities.
An American remake with plenty of new pizazz.
One of those rare motion pictures with side-splitting laughs where the humor never stays dormant for long.
What makes Mike Nichols' version more than just a retread is good casting in the key roles, and a wicked screenplay by Elaine May, who keeps the original story but adds little zingers here and there.
Basically, the movie's an extended setup for a dinner-table comedy of errors, in which the mismatched relatives confront one another in a nerve-racking test of appearances.
The interchanges and conversation are hilarious, and the comedy continues to build until the movie's implausible but humorous end.
This movie is THE definition of average. Not bad, but not good.
This critic admired Robin Williams's performance as well as some of the minor actors, but found the film's depiction of gay people more insulting to them than funny.
A bit of a letdown in some ways, The Birdcage nonetheless features some scene-stealing performances.

The Birdcage is a funny film, with terrific performances by headliners Robin Williams, as an aging gay man, and Gene Hackman and Dianne Wiest as an uptight conservative couple he hosts at a dinner party while trying to act straight.
Far less plastic than most cross-dressing comedies.
It's a rare event when a remake of a film rivals the greatness of the original.
Nathan Lane, I would personally like to send you a big, fat kiss of admiration.
The result is a nearly flavorless 118 minutes punctuated with a few hilarious scenes -- mostly owed to the physical comedy of stage actor Nathan Lane.
Barb Wire isn't much when it comes to either deliberate or inadvertent humor.
The element of high camp that makes for enjoyable 'good trash' isn't present. Bad movies like this often generate small cult followings, and that's about the size of audience the picture deserves.
There's as much sheer work in this film as in films 10 times as good -- which is both encouraging and depressing, I suppose.
Director David Hogan keeps the action moving and loaded with fights, gun battles and other action-trashy thrills.
The whole film is nothing more than just a tease, not worth the bother.
Forget straight to video. This should have been straight to hell.
It is, after all, a comic book come to life (it's based on the Dark Horse comic series) and doesn't pretend to be about anything more than that.
Buxom babes, big explosions, and black leather. Hey, pal, what more do you want?

There's something sad about Lee purposely sculpting her breasts to resemble basketballs, then parading around topless or nearly topless for most of the film, while her character is supposed to comically strike a blow for feminism.
The movie is predominantly a sexual tease, albeit one without appreciably more nudity than you can see in 1968's Barbarella.
A convoluted mess, but there have been worse.
The hypocrisy level is annoying.
Mr. Lee isn't as successful at shaping a story around Girl 6, but enjoying her company is all his slender, sunny film really tries to do.
Lee may have a keen sense of setting and dialogue, but his characterization is off.
Lee draws his lines between fantasy and reality without much confidence and with only a sketchy logic.
Instead of effervescent and mercurial, the movie is simply muddled. What happened?
Strongly told stories have a way of carrying their characters along with them. But here we have an undefined character in an aimless story. Too bad.
Erratic, at times predictable as hell, and at other times unruly and inventive.
Girl 6 has all the subtle yuks of an Al Sharpton sermon and nearly half the tender honesty of Mike Tyson.
The main character is never well-defined, the drama often seems half-hearted, and the comedy repeatedly falls flat.
Frenetic but lazily conceived, it's like one of those puny low-budget toss-offs Brian De Palma used to spring on us when he thought nobody was looking.
Lee sculpts every scene precisely in his story of a woman growing out of her 20-something aimlessness.
Isn't anything more than a sloppy showcase for the group's costume-changing tricks, but sometimes its sheer chutzpah can be amusing.
Reader, I did not laugh.
[A] shrill and slovenly opus.
Transitorily amusing and as a sophomoric display of crude humor, is funny.
It's like one long sketch that never seems to rocket off into the inspired heights of lunacy the series maintained so well.
I do get it. I just don't like it.
Some of this is very funny; much of it isn't.
Good characters in a crummy story don't make for particularly good time, but there are plenty of laughs to be had by all scattered throughout the film.
A sleek, whooshingly entertaining update of the vintage television series.
This movie isn't a disaster, but, all things considered, there's little reason to make it a high priority for theatrical viewing.
Every effect is so calculated that only the conscious minds of filmmakers and viewers are engaged--and not by very much or for very long.
The film is painful in at least one way - its waste of good actors.
A sleek, stunningly made movie.
Tom Cruise looks cool and holds our attention while doing neat things that we don't quite understand.
A fun and diverting summer movie, well worth the price of admission.
Too devious for its own good.
There are just a few groovy special effects and a practically incomprehensible story which we finally can't work up enough energy to care about.
Exciting, smart and enormously enjoyable.

Improbable but highly entertaining suspense yarn.

Overblown in every sense. At times this is a plus.
An infinite trailer that is all effects, no affect.

Once it gets going, A Thin Line is moderately entertaining, but, oh my, that first hour...
Martin Lawrence bites off a bit more than he can chew with his four roles in this haphazard comedy. As a result, nothing seems quite focused.
Sexual stereotyping provides the grist for much of Martin Lawrence's humor and, for the most part, it's on target.
Lawrence the director should have pulled the reigns in on Lawrence the star, as his constant mugging is both out of character and ridiculously exaggerated.

A Thin Line Between Love and Hate takes its name from the Persuaders 1971 hit that has been re-recorded by the Pretenders, Annie Lennox and H-Town. You could have just as much fun simply playing one of them and skipping the movie.
[Lawrence] doesn't seem to know that his protagonist is a deceptive, frivolous, fast-talking and surprisingly stupid womanizer.
Like the original 1963 movie and the TV series, it expects us to be endlessly amused by a dolphin that does things that are endless but not amusing.
Flipper is inoffensive, but it's also asleep in the deep.

Erratically paced but generally provocative.
I had a lot of trouble trying to figure out why this picture was made. What was the director trying to accomplish?
Though this terrifically cast movie may prove a tad too detached even for some members of its targeted audience, it covers remarkable ground in less than two hours.
