Streep and Keaton, in their different styles, find ways to make Lee and Bessie into much more than the expression of their problems.
Marvin's Room seems to exist primarily to road-test every one of your emotions.
A terminal illness movie that doesn't beat you over the head with overwrought sentimentality
Any dramatic film can go wrong if it doesn't completely ring true, and Marvin's Room misses the mark.
The movie's tone is mostly mushy and tearjerking, bounced occasionally into a tighter, more sardonic humor by DiCaprio andKeaton's performances.
It is of higher class than any made for TV melodrama but falls short of being the next Steel Magnolias or Awakenings. Great actors do what they can in a simple and largely unaffecting story.
Well acted, but not often believable, dysfunctional family drama.
An emotionally fulfilling film with wonderful, uplifting elements.
Without the humor, the film would have been unwatchably morose.
In many ways it looks an awful lot like one of those generic made-for-TV disease-of-week movies.
DiCaprio is maturing into a fine actor who looks like a slender young Bill Clinton.

Kidman shapes a finely detailed portrait of Isabel as she shifts from a high- spirited, rather careless, red-white- and-blue Yank in England to a fearful, drawn, pale captive in Rome. Yet Campion's film suffers from its arty inclinations.
The Portrait of a Lady is a difficult story to film, and Jane Campion and screenwriter Laura Jones have done an admirable job with this adaptation.
Kidman comes up with tones of hurt and resolve and poise and warmth that she has never shown before.

If you're bored to distraction with safe, unimaginative movie versions of great books, take heart: Jane Campion's bold and brilliant rendering of Henry James' masterpiece has single-handedly raised the high-water mark of literary adaptations.
A lesser director might not have dared make the bodies and things and places of Portrait of a Lady so tactile. But Jane Campion understands James.
Kidman is one of the chilliest actresses on-screen today. Which may explain her success in To Die For and her failure here.
Alternately hypnotic and fascinating, then puzzling and boring.
What we have instead is an ambitious effort that works only in patches. If this movie is a portrait, it's a fuzzy one.
Jane Campion's adaptation of the 19th-century Henry James novel, The Portrait of a Lady, has much going for it -- including actress Nicole Kidman. But, ultimately, it disappoints.
The Portrait of a Lady, alas, is a still-life without figures.
The Portrait of a Lady is a serious, not to say solemn piece of work by a director of uncommon talent, and it disappoints in the way that only such ambitious work can.
reviewUrl: The Portrait of a Lady is a serious, not to say solemn piece of work by a director of uncommon talent, and it disappoints in the way that only such ambitious work can.

reviewText: Using hallucinatory cinematic techniques, Campion spells out the wrenching entrapment of her heroine, Isabel Archer, in a series of striking images that disturb, entice, haunt and dazzle.
A coy New Age prologue, an early dream sequence, and a surrealist black-and-white interlude are at best provocative teasers for an alternative to James that never takes shape.
Intelligent but exasperating, its monotonous tone will wear down even viewers who started out in its corner.
Kidman is really coming into her own as a true talent, as well, and the remaining cast are all great.
Barbara Hershey's complex turn as the mysterious Mme. Merle, who lives as a virtual captive to Osmond's power, is the only performance with much emotional resonance.
As a treatment of the story, as an evocation of the emotions of love and the wound of betrayal, it is close to Puccini's intentions, and very moving.

Besides a visual combination of authentic Japanese realism and picturesque, dream-like cinematography that matches the lushness of Puccini's music, director Frederic Mitterrand gives the opera a distinctively cinematic gravity and subtlety.
An involving, intimate portrait of a group of men gathered for a common purpose.
If the movie's central sadness is that we identify with our own group and suspect outsiders, the movie's message is that we have been given brains to learn to empathize.
A feat of metaphor and rhetoric.
Spike Lee has returned to his cinematic roots here, his cinematic flair not disguised by his own sense of self-righteousness.
Most of the show is a talkfest heading no place in particular. Only the bus has a direction.

Spike Lee's one-year anniversary commemoration of the Million Man March is a smart, funny, passionate, and open-ended tribute to the spirit of the unprecedented gathering that so galvanized the hearts and minds of African-American men.
It takes far too many dead-end detours, is devoid of real characters and can be justly accused of being both sexist and anti-Semitic.
If the movie finally doesn't know when to quit, its flaws are those of enthusiasm and heart.
There's nothing quite like watching a film in which every person on the screen offers up their heart and soul for the sake of the picture -- and that's just what happens here.
Sequels are a chancy business at best, but The Evening Star is thin and contrived.
The script is by the director Robert Harding, and all his jokes fall like stones.
There is an absolute poetry to the casting of Tom Cruise as Jerry Maguire.
This is the kind of movie that reminds me why I started reviewing in the first place.
Cameron Crowe, Tom Cruise, and Cuba Gooding Jr. are salesmen, and we're consumers, buying emotional truth. That's a brave message for a commercial film to have. Too bad it's unintentional.
There are a couple of moments in Jerry Maguire when you want to hug yourself with delight.
Gooding does his finest work since Boyz N the Hood, positively glowing with this character's mixture of engaging brassiness and (occasionally misdirected) energy.
Cruise has never been this open or this funny.
Jerry Maguire is a lovely film, and an extremely fun film full of moment-to-moment observation.
Zellweger's sweetly intense performance is a star-making one, while Gooding shines in his fast-talking charm.
Jerry Maguire ranks among the precious few films that manage to invoke the full spectrum of human emotion while appearing neither contrived nor insincere.
Cruise is at the top of his form, and Gooding makes a brilliant opponent.

[Crowe] successfully balances one of the best performances of Tom Cruise's career with a clutch of superb supporting turns. Add a witty and tear-jerking script and the result is an unusual romantic comedy drama.
What follows is predictable, the ways of love and friendship and underdog struggles and cute kids in Hollywood being what they are. But Crowe and company pull it off with a wink and a prayer.
Jerry Maguire is a romantic comedy that delivers everything it promises.
You could do far worse than the quest for a reasonable adult happiness.
I'd love to see more movies like Jerry Maguire, movies that show us that making a life for oneself is not only is it possible but preferable.
Director Cameron Crowe has written and directed a deft, funny, shamelessly upbeat romantic comedy and to top it all drawn out the finest performance of Tom Cruise's career.
Director Cameron Crowe nearly fumbles the ball with an overabundance of situations and subplots, but is rescued by the starpower of his actors.
A feel-good movie that satisfies emotionally.
I just couldn't buy into the redemption of Jerry Maguire.
Overall Jerry Maguire is an enjoyable film, but far from a memorable one.
Jerry Maguire is, ultimately, a failed idealism.
You may come away from Jerry Maguire feeling a little dizzy, but once the film settles into afterthought, it provides plenty to think about.
One of those tempting sugar confections you devour halfway through before recognizing the strange new taste sensations at the center.
Slick, stylish and committed.
The combination of Crowe's exceptional script and the superior cast, highlighted by Cruise's flawless performance, results in one of the years most substantial movies.
A slightly flawed gem.
It talks the talk but doesn't walk the walk. Or, in other words, it simply doesn't have heart.
Cameron Crowe's overstuffed but exuberantly humane Jerry Maguire is a Tom Cruise vehicle that gives equal time to brilliantly cast co-stars in elaborately conceived roles.
Traces of Crowe's now-trademark style of filmmaking are evident here, making Maguire a sort of launching pad for what we hope are better things to come.
Jerry Maguire is a savvy depiction of a punched-up egomaniac being mauled by the tender hands of love.
Jerry Maguire is slick but not quite believable.
Here is a remarkable exception to the proven principle that all movies with any scene taking place at a football game are stinkers.
'Drunks' is a thoroughly unsentimental group portrait of people in various stages of recovery struggling with the same inner demons that torment all of us.
An uninspired formula movie with another fine performance by Michelle Pfeiffer.
Our whole family loved it.
One Fine Day is two formulaic hours, but they do illustrate how two attractive leads and a lickety-split narrative can elevate meager material into something this side of bearability.
Represents a keen, personal look at the difficulties of growing up gay in a heterosexual world.
The boys' lives contain few surprises ... but from the other characters there is one astonishment after another.
Beautiful Thing isn't particularly deep, nor is it a great piece of filmmaking, but it's so sweet-natured and well-acted that it's hard to resist.
Reminds me of some of Jonathan Demme's early movies, where ordinary people are celebrated for their eccentricities but not condescended to.
The performances are mostly quite good, but the script definitely needs work.
If Beautiful Thing were any more sensitive, it would faint.
In portraying romance, the film transcends its homosexual themes, while at the same time celebrating them.
Manages to do what few films have done -- convey coming out with the specificity that draws viewers in while conveying a universality that hits home.
This is a moving and challenging movie, fascinated by the murky depths that separate what people want from what they say they want and what they think they should want.
The first movie I have seen that does not improve on the sight of a blank screen viewed for the same length of time.
A stunning feat of literary adaptation as well as a purely cinematic triumph.

This is one of the year's most unabashed and powerful love stories, using flawless performances, intelligent dialogue, crisp camera work, and loaded glances to attain a level of eroticism and emotional connection that many similar films miss.
The English Patient, the superb new film by Anthony Minghella, is that rarest of things: a film based on a great contemporary novel.

This poetic, evocative film version of the famous novel by Michael Ondaatje circles down through layers of mystery until all of the puzzles in the story have been solved, and only the great wound of a doomed love remains.
This is a movie to lose yourself in.
The English Patient's heart may be in the right place, but the fire is lacking.
Haunting and enthralling.
It does not deserve limitless adoration. Just quiet, reasoned admiration.
The English Patient is a labyrinthine film, with plenty of mysteries and secrets all around, and it is a film not to be missed.
This masterful piece of cinema showcases the talents of some of the screen's best.
There's much suffering here, and the film is most interesting when it (infrequently) ditches a traditional emphasis on nobility and gets on with it.
It is rare to see a movie where images and visual textures play such an important role, not merely as decoration, but as substance and metaphor.
By the end of the film, the mysteries are resolved, the characters have stolen your heart, and two great romances have blossomed.
The English Patient is one for the ages.
Despite its lengthy running time and occasionally languid pace, The English Patient feels brief and dreamlike.
A fine, passionate film, but not, in my opinion, the masterpiece that it's so clearly straining to be.
It didn't quite make my top 10 list, but it is not bad.
The film is enjoyable to watch -- even visually stunning in places -- but the muted emotions limit the moviegoing experience.
An aerobic workout for the tear ducts.
Highly, highly recommended.
The English Patient is the kind of movie that makes you want to interpret everything you see, that makes you keenly aware that everything can have meaning.
Minghella is a master of detail.

It isn't the best picture of the year, it isn't film-making as it is supposed to be. But it is heart-breakingly poetic, it is beautifully directed and acted, and it is a brilliant film that is only slightly derailed by its own breadth and scope.
Palookaville understands a kind of low-key humor based on human nature.
Following in the wake of a trio of disappointing features, First Contact proves to be the most entertaining Star Trek in more than a decade.
Star Trek: First Contact is one of the best of the eight Star Trek films: Certainly the best in its technical credits, and among the best in the ingenuity of its plot.
A thoroughly enjoyable visit with the crew of TV's Star Trek: The Next Generation.
It's a great movie, and a great story.
One of the better entries in the Trek movie series, thanks to the most memorable villains from the Next Generation television series: the Borg
If you don't already know and enjoy Star Trek, this is nothing more than another passable science fiction film. If you are a fan of The Next Generation, then you'll enjoy this one.
Enough classic moments to keep fans happy.
First Contact manages to rev some additional life into the series.
It is enjoyable. It is a must-see for Star Trek fans. But it is not cohesive enough to be a good movie.
A good popcorn movie.
Even if you don't count yourself as trekkie you should see it.

The first stretch and the home stretch are so filled with visual interest and, more importantly, with the patented Star Trek philosophical and humorous tidbits that fans will gladly suffer the dull Borg patch for the pleasure of the rest.
The film feels soulless and hollow, despite best intentions to the contrary.
Deftly combining parts of Alien, Moby Dick and Close Encounters of the Third Kind, First Contact starts quickly and doesn't let up.
This is a film that all the millions of Star Trek fans will treasure as one of the best in the now eight-film history of this hopeful future myth.
The most exciting entry in the Trek franchise since the The Wrath Of Khan.

For non-Trekkers, this is a great, free-standing special-effects adventure with much more fleshy characters than your average sci-fi yarn. Definitely a good ride. But there are also plenty of nods to Star Trek aficionados.

Breaking the Waves is emotionally and spiritually challenging, hammering at conventional morality with the belief that God not only sees all, but understands a great deal more than we give Him credit for.
As frustrating as it is rewarding, this makes compulsive viewing nonetheless.

The acting is flawless, but it is Emily Watson who delivers the film's emotional powder keg. The cinematography is outstanding and the setting mesmerising - all powered by a spare but powerful script. It is a true marvel of a movie.
The movie is looking to make you feel yucky, and it does.
A haunting, brutal fairy tale, this masterfully detailed character study is uncompromising and emotionally exhausting. It's a great movie.
Hardy art-film moviegoers may want to check it out, if only for Watson's transcendent performance. But anyone who gets nauseated at the thought of a boat ride should think twice.
Von Trier staves off the inherent tawdriness of his concept and invests it with a fierce gravity.
Watson's Bess is an unforgettable character -- simple, profound, heartbreaking, tragic and yet triumphant.
Quite simply the most emotionally devastating film I have ever seen....There is no better example of why film is such a powerful medium.

Michael doesn't set up big drama or punch up big moments. It ambles. Travolta, using the same offhand ease that worked in Phenomenon, works his magic on the humans without even seeming to have his mind much on his job.
Dammit, but I'm tired of movies in which the dog is the most believable, most complex character (not to insult the dog, who actually shows a range of emotions).

In Love and War is not much interested in Ernest Hemingway's subsequent life and career, and even in its treatment of this early period, it doesn't deal with themes such as his macho posturing, his need to prove himself, his grandiosity.
Can a film be saved by its music?

In Love and War is at its best photographing stationary objects, such as architecture, trees and bedridden soldiers -- not exactly what one hopes for from a movie portraying such a vital force as Ernest Hemingway.
A stillborn affair that could have been -- and should have been -- a whole lot hipper and funnier.
As light entertainment, Mars Attacks! gave me more pleasure than most other recent movies I've seen.
A throwaway piece of pop ephemera, like a '90s Casino Royale, momentarily arresting and soon forgotten.
First he made Ed Wood, a tribute to the man fondly recalled as the worst movie director of all time. Now Tim Burton seems to have made a tribute to Wood's work.
Sadly empty exercise.
If movies have pop cult I.Q.s, Mars Attacks scores somewhere beyond 200.
Heavy with irony and criss-cross cultural references, Mars Attacks! betrays the same fondness for schlock that has marked much of Burton's work.
Mars Attacks! is the film that Independence Day wanted to be but never could be.
Unlike Burton's tribute to B-movie director Ed Wood or Mel Brooks' parody Young Frankenstein, this movie's self-awareness doesn't work.

With Mars Attacks, director Tim Burton has created not only an instant cult hit, but a very offbeat black comedy that parodies martian invasion films, disaster films, and many aspects of our popular culture.
Flaming white hot death to anyone involved in this crappy film!
Galactic hoards of fun, but slightly disappointing bubble-gum sci-fi flick.
Mars Attacks! is not so much a spoof of 'B' science fiction films as it is an homage to them. But those 'B' films were usually bad, and this homage to them suffers for the same reasons.
Like a well-constructed bad painting, there is much to admire in the film, but the net effect leaves you dispassionate.
While Mars Attacks! may not have been as good as it could have been, it is definitely one of the better sci-fi flicks to have headed our way in quite a while.

A holiday film with no conscience whatsoever, Mars Attacks! will make you laugh, it will make you cry, and it definitely will make you wonder about Earth's ability to defend itself in the face of higher life forms.
The film's penchant for repetition is faithful to its '50s source material and is the very quality that turns Mars Attacks! into such a marvelously unstable comedy.
Despite the very slow start, Mars Attacks! delivers the goods.
I can only report that I've now seen the film twice, and that I laughed my fool head off both times from beginning to end.
An acquired taste.

Isolated cool moments aside, Mars Attacks! is mostly blah filler. Burton dashes around so skittishly he rarely has time to exploit his better ideas; it's not the sustained kitschy romp the excellent trailers lead you to expect.
Nothing much is funny in Mars Attacks!, whose mildly amusing War of the Worlds story can best be described as... Mars attacks.
This messy masterpiece is the year's funniest comedy and a weird, winking affirmation of the power of the people.
John Waters will weep with envy.
As sci-fi spoofs go, Mars Attacks! may never be topped.
Dangerous Ground begins with a promising idea and runs away from it as fast as it can.
Violent melodrama.
Full of jokes that fall flat.
The first half hour in particular is clogged with wheezing routines that appear to have no punchlines.
Chase unrolls his tired collection of mugs and stumbles, while some truly funny performers - particularly Sid Caesar and the usually reliable Wallace Shawn - are wasted in do-nothing roles.
So far from funny it's actually painful to sit through.
There should be a self-help group where insecure people make themselves feel better by constantly repeating: "He's Chevy Chase and I'm not."
This is not the sort of comedy that asks much of a viewer, and it's not as if you have to engage your brain.
Somewhere along the way, the filmmakers lost sight of what made the original Vacation funny. It wasn't the actual goal... but the journey.
This is one vacation that went off the rails from the outset.
The central idea of the series -- even normal families aren't normal -- apparently isn't completely exhausted yet. I'm surprised at how much I liked this film.
Retracing overly traveled roads.
The film's only life is provided by Randy Quaid, back as Ellen's redneck cousin.
Why, if [Chevy] Chase is such a funny guy, does he make such unfunny movies?
Now here is a gangster movie that does not want setups or payoffs like traditional gangster movies.
The picture works despite the bizarre ending.
Call it Bad Mafia Lieutenant.
Nobody spins a good morality yarn like Abel Ferrara.
We have seen Martin Scorsese's gangster films, and Abel Ferrara, you are no Martin Scorsese.
Film after film, Ferrara and St. John are finding new ways to scream.
Ferrara's eerie version of crime-wracked New York City of the 1930s.
A fairly routine thriller that gets high marks as a result of tight pacing and top-notch acting.
The picture might have gotten by if Eastwood had given it some impudent wit. But he directs to the rhythm of his facial muscles.
Not many thrillers slow down to notice relationships, but this one does.
The script calls for no bold statements about the politics of the White House, which makes the film rather weak in purpose.
This is just a better makeup job on the same misogynist theme: live woman = nothing; dead woman = power.
Lacks the consistency, depth and suspense that would put it in a league with Eastwood's best work.
Dramatically and cinematically, the film is fabulous until the final third of its two hours, when everyone tries a tad too hard, from scriptwriter to director.
Clint Eastwood...produced, directed and stars in this generally lunatic, occasionally pathetic and more often comically inept endeavor.
It's refreshing to think that good movies can still be made with only actors, a tight script, and some nice locations.
Besides the ridiculousness of the plot, some of the acting is terrible. Embarrassingly bad as the President, Hackman wastes his great talent on a poorly written character.
Sadly, any lofty artistic aspirations are quickly undone by the sheer ill-advised audacity of the story.
Unintentional yuks litter an otherwise somber political thriller adapted from David Baldacci's novel.
Eastwood is perfect as the bad guy you root for because he isn't nearly as bad as the other bad guys.
Two old guys, sitting on a bench, talking for two hours. That's my rewrite.
The beauty of the language does come through, but the net effect of the movie is to make the viewers wish they had gone to the play instead.

This is good stuff. Unfortunately, director Herb Gardner is a little too fond of writer Herb Gardner's script, which just keeps going and going and going -- until even two old pros such as Walter and Ossie have worn out their welcome.
A crisp spy thriller.

This looks like the setup for a story of proletarian bliss, but in fact Caught is the most carnal of recent movies, a film that reminds us how movies used to take sex seriously, instead of using it as an excuse for muscular choreography.

Hotel de Love is a pleasant and sometimes funny film, without being completely satisfying. It is too twee. Too many lines are said for their cuteness, too many exchanges sound like a comedy routine, and the movie works too earnestly at being daffy.
A fine motion picture.
[Thornton] performance is so good that his directing may be slighted.
By its midpoint, however, Thornton has begun forcing both the film's poetry and the preternatural goodness of its simple-minded protagonist, and Sling Blade's sweet charms begin to curdle.
If there were the slightest justice and curiosity in the Academy Award process, Thornton's work here would get a nomination.
[Thornton] does wonders with Yoakam, who could have played a standard villain but always manages to suggest a man trapped within his prejudices.
The lure of Sling Blade is both elemental and hauntingly familiar, and I would not be surprised if Thornton's breakthrough film is one day considered a classic in its own right.
In Sling Blade, Thornton lays claim to the title of hyphenate of the year.
Sling Blade takes you down paths full of primitive, almost biblical implications, but it also finds comic relief in moments of palpable tension.
American films rarely depict the lower-class milieu as respectfully as this unsentimental drama.
Ambivalence reigns in Sling Blade. For every funny moment there is a shocking revelation. For every cute bit of dialogue interplay there is a disturbing recollection.
[C]athartic in its own way... Karl, living in his own twisted moral world, could take it upon himself to prevent future harm to those he cared about by eliminating the source of their misery.
Sling Blade gives you plenty to think about, and neither the story nor the quality of the film can easily be forgotten.
It will make you laugh and cry. And it will make you think long and hard about the last time you saw a movie this good.
Billy Bob Thornton has created a great American original, a fascinating character who is both victim and savior.
Everything is overly telegraphed, and you can see where the movie is going from a mile away, but it is worth the journey to discover a character like Karl.
This is the best movie I have seen in a long time.
If you like films where the acting takes center stage, then Sling Blade is the film for you.
Sling Blade does homage to Psycho without slavishly imitating the memorable parts.
There is a lot of rich atmosphere here, and Thornton's own central performance is riveting.
A real gem.
All the actors in Sling Blade do magnificent work, but it's Thornton who stays with you for days.
If you can adjust to Thornton's extremely mannered performance, the piece is effectively chilly.
Thornton's performance is riveting.
This would be an ideal movie for parents and children to see together, and talk about afterward. Shiloh, like all great family films, deals with real issues in real ways.
A smart, well-made buddy film about two junkies desperate to kick the habit.
Gridlock'd is refreshing because it's different. The subject matter isn't new, but the approach and tone are.
A surprisingly light-hearted comedy about what happens when two self-imposed exiles from society decide to go straight and look to the system for a little help.
This is grim material, but surprisingly entertaining, and it is more cause to mourn the recent death of Shakur, who gives his best performance as Spoon, a musician who wants to get off drugs.

A hard-edged, darkly funny satire about two Detroit junkies who discover if they want to go straight, they'll have to climb a Mt. Everest of forms, paperwork, office referrals, waiting rooms, rules and regulations.
A black, but certainly not a bleak, comedy, Gridlock'd is a wonderfully realized comment on the entanglements of beaurocracy at its most ridiculous.
Tupac Shakur turned in an excellent final performance.
Gridlock'd is a seemingly low budget film that covers the same ground as Trainspotting, but not as imaginatively.
The film does occasionally lapse into silly slapstick and caricature, but most of the way this is a tough, funny and scary cautionary tale.
So just when Roth and Shakur's clowning closeness nearly transcends the subject, the film throws up a bunch of flashy edits and MTV-esque close-ups that trivialize it. Junkies just can't win.
Made piecemeal over a number of years and first released in 1983, this 90-minute comic fantasy has lost little of its radical edge.
The underlying lesson is clear: Our state and federal farm policies do not really allow for family farms anymore.
It's not perfect, but "Troublesome Creek" gets by on the charming personality of it subjects.
Anybody with a feeling for the rural Midwest will find this visually engaging documentary a bittersweet reminder of how family farming, once a pillar of American life, is slowly vanishing.
By subtly painting portraits of her parents and brothers and sisters, we also witness a remarkable history filled with noble examples of how to live, work, age and love in America today.
Because its ideas remain murky, it frustrates our expectations. It's not a satisfying film, but that doesn't make it a bad one.
An odd and beautiful film about a pilgrimage to a desolate land.
Cold Fever is thoroughly quirky and unusual, and one-hundred-percent experiential. You've got to sweat it out in order to get to the other side.
Cold Fever serves a useful function right there: It shows an Icelandic winter close up, and it's a lot more fascinating than you might expect.
It's difficult to review a movie that is really just an introduction to something far larger and more complex.
Four words. Underplayed boring Jackie Chan.
It's all so... Jackie, and if you're a fan, you won't be disappointed.
Crime Story proves that even as he gets older and eschews his clown persona, Jackie Chan is an action star to reckon with. Fans will not be disappointed.
It's the kind of movie where every paying customer deserves to receive a handwritten apology from the producers.
This movie defies review. To critique it would be like writing about a restaurant that only serves birdseed. Of course, humans don't like birdseed -- it's not meant for our species.
By their nature, pests are meant to get under your skin and this one certainly does.
A revoltingly bad stinker that is easily in the running for the worst film of the decade.
Quick, someone find a no-pest strip - or even a fly swatter or a good bug spray.
This film is utterly without discipline or focus in a way that -- to one's shame --one eventually finds oddly endearing.
Obviously, someone must have told Leguizamo he's a comic genius. Whoever did that isn't his friend.
It lacks the hair-trigger timing, the headlong rush into comic illogic, that made Wanda so special. But it does have a charm of its own, and moments of wicked inspiration.
[T]ries to have its cake and eat it, too - and it mostly succeeds. At least it fills a void until the next Monty Python movie.

The spirited cast of Jamie Lee Curtis, Kevin Kline and Monty Pythonites John Cleese and Michael Palin is willing. But this tossed-together trifle about an unassuming British zoo taken over by a money-mad Murdochian media mogul is weak.
Here is a movie so absorbing, so atmospheric, so suspenseful and so dumb, that it proves my point: The subject matter doesn't matter in a movie nearly as much as mood, tone and style.
This tough-to-peg whodunit keeps you going for two hours, despite a few James Bond-ish (or Jane Bond-ish) turns that play less preposterously than you might assume were they to be divulged.
Farley might want to be like John Candy, but, while Candy knew how to make an audience laugh, Farley keeps missing the mark.
This formulaic tale of a ninja klutz trying to break a counterfeit ring can be recommended only to undemanding children, and even they may find it a drag.
There's at least one consolation: David Spade is not in the movie.
The funfest comes with an OFF warning -- Only For Farleymeisters.
A surprisingly boring comedy.
An extremely unfunny vehicle for Chris Farley.
The humor the premise throws off is supposed to be funny. It just isn't.
A silly movie, with silly jokes and a silly story. But the talents at work in it are not silly.

You don't have to be a sports fan to enjoy this.... All you need is an appreciation of recent history and a desire to learn more about an event that had far more importance in the world's eyes than any other heavyweight bout in the history of boxing.

With the odds seemingly stacked against him, and surrounded by press, performers, crooks, and charlatans of every stripe, Ali triumphed, and he did so by staying true to his vision and trusting in his own talents.
Anyone who sees it and still thinks that the sport is two guys beating each other up just ain't paying attention.
There is a palpable tension, as the two men step into the ring, that is not lessened because we know the outcome.
By the time the fighters enter that ring, the excitement factor is almost uncontrollable.
Capturing Ali's legendary charm and enthusiasm, the moment is utterly enchanting. He's stunning here, to-die-for charismatic, terrifically entertaining and confident.
One of the best and most emotionally affecting documentaries ever made.
To think of this marvelous film as merely a boxing documentary is to miss a lot.
A thoroughly entertaining documentary about a clash between boxing legends.
A good example of able filmmakers staying out of the way of a very interesting subject.

Leon Gast's ability as a filmmaker is perhaps best demonstrated when he manages to make the strategy and the execution of the fight both lucid and interesting. He does this through a series of interviews that are done in voice-over during the fight.
Beyond creating an exceptional documentary, Gast reminds us of the majesty of Muhammad Ali, a man who was, and is, a hero for the ages.
A distinct sense of melancholy arises from this ebullient music and Gast's brilliant reportage of an event so joyous and heady.
[Ali's] a riot, and this film made me laugh more frequently than most of the outright comedies I've seen this year.

What a wonderful world. Sure, people cheat on each other. But they also act honorably and speak honestly and admit the darkest secrets about themselves. This sort of movie might bore you to tears, but it also might be just what you've longed for.

Gray's Anatomy finds Spalding Gray turning a bout with a bizarre ocular condition into a dizzying, absorbing odyssey of the neurotic mind.
If you cannot see Spalding Gray live, then do see his monologue films. Gray's Anatomy can be infuriating, but Spalding makes it worthwhile.
Not only is it interesting to follow the course of Gray's storyline, the movie is also equally interesting to view, even if the storyteller is just sitting in front of a desk most of the time.

If you've seen and enjoyed either or both of the two previous movies adapted from Spalding Gray's monologues, Swimming to Cambodia and Monster in a Box, then you're more or less guaranteed to enjoy Gray's Anatomy.
The film manages to come off like a dinnertime conversation with a friend -- albeit a one-sided and long but very good and very funny one.
